commit_message:
Make sure the converted image is imported

Turns out the converted image is being completely ignored. This is
because the `file_path` provided by the ImportToFS task cannot be
overriden by other tasks. In order to fix this, I've dropped all the
extra suffixes that we've been using in favor of working on the actual
`file_path` directly.

Change-Id: Ifbd2308057f33c1f712fa06f9bb3e57f90068fdc
Closes-bug: #1452750
(cherry picked from commit d77fd685ea4d552eb4cf6c5c4a1049ed7964ff05)

commit_message:
Add capability to save more than 10 logfiles per CI run

By default, the logging is setup to save 10 logfiles after it begins rotating
them. This change makes that configurable, with a default of 40. Note this is
only enabled if you have debug turned on.

Change-Id: I11c2df266181146577c5d98131180b177b912149
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Fix xmldsig import

After commit https://goo.gl/TjLQFz to pysaml2, xmldsig was moved
under saml2, no longer being at the top level. Craeting a
conditional import, so it can work now and when the pysaml2
commit is included in a new release.

Conflicts:
	keystone/tests/unit/test_v3_federation.py

Change-Id: If01a93a18cef6159adad50496e6335e88f86024d
(cherry picked from commit c90dd3a0f8280e28bbbff691c0ae27aff736658a)

[{'created': '2015-06-15 17:39:35.000000000', 'message': 'Fix TestObjEqualPrims test object registration

The way objects are registered was changed in commit
d95c05a8fd2f762765408b9cf84da7c8d34a7892 so that test objects were
no longer automatically registered. This meant that they now have
to be explicitly registered. The MyObj test object in
nova.tests.unit.object.test_objects is registered in
_BaseTestCase.setup() for convienience. Unfortunately
TestObjEqualPrims did not extend _BaseTestCase so it missed the
registration and so the tests are invalid.

This fixes the tests by making them extend _BaseTestCase.

Closes-Bug: #1465344

Change-Id: Ibfd4d81f9aecbd3628193cf47688ab3ac28090db
'}]
commit_message:
Fix TestObjEqualPrims test object registration

The way objects are registered was changed in commit
d95c05a8fd2f762765408b9cf84da7c8d34a7892 so that test objects were
no longer automatically registered. This meant that they now have
to be explicitly registered. The MyObj test object in
nova.tests.unit.object.test_objects is registered in
_BaseTestCase.setup() for convienience. Unfortunately
TestObjEqualPrims did not extend _BaseTestCase so it missed the
registration and so the tests are invalid.

This fixes the tests by making them extend _BaseTestCase.

Closes-Bug: #1465344

Change-Id: Ibfd4d81f9aecbd3628193cf47688ab3ac28090db

commit_message:
Create a Glance-specific VIP for Pacemaker HA

This change modifies the parameters that determine which virtual IP
the Glance API uses. If there are no isolated networks, the virtual IP
on the 'ctlplane' network will be used. If the isolated network that
is referenced in ServiceNetMap for the Glance API exists, then a VIP
will be created on that network for Glance.

Change-Id: I91b0f3896e2acf1637de66ab9a95d0eed9304c02

commit_message:
Fix the problem with ceph deployment on scale lab

Postpone ceph pool creation to post deploy:
* Add task for ceph pool creation and put it in post deploy
* Change ceph/compute.pp and move to post deploy
* Remove from ceph/manifests/init.pp the pool creation code

Closes-bug: #1462451
Change-Id: Iee72e5f8e59c3ced0ba0d7f971380e5932cbb0fc

commit_message:
Reflect project moves from stackforge to openstack.

Several git repos were just moved from stackforge to openstack.
Reflect the move in various places where the URL was in docs and
comments.  In passing, also change URLs to git.openstack.org instead
of github, as that is the official home of all of these repos.

Change-Id: I6c79a192d6604cef01e88d5b305fcc2b0f9c6b30
Co-Authored-By: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Add an index to virtual_interfaces.uuid

Performance issues have been reported such
that the query performed by virtual_interface_get_by_uuid
becomes prohibitively slow after a large (~250K) number of instances
have been created, and an attempt is made to launch instances
in batch.  An index added to uuid shows a dramatic improvement
to this query in EXPLAIN testing.

This is the master branch which adds the migration as #294.

Change-Id: I912e5a01ac63f2a7ab5533e9b6ff8738af819d67
Closes-bug: #1445675

commit_message:
Merge tag '2014.2'

This is a null-merge of the 2014.2 release tag back into the
master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try

commit_message:
Merge tag '2015.1.0'

This is a null-merge of the 2015.1.0 release tag back into the master
branch so that the 2015.1.0 tag will appear in the git commit history of
the master branch. It contains no actual changes to the master branch,
regardless of how our code review system's UI represents it. Please
ask in #openstack-infra if you have any questions, and otherwise try
to merge this as quickly as possible to avoid later conflicts on the
master branch.

Change-Id: Ifbe5418d35b042c5e6ef72443c21340a524db3fa

commit_message:
Execute specified tasks only for particular contoroller

>> fuel node --node 2 --tasks netconfig
Will execute task only on provided node, without additional controllers

But

>> fuel node --node 2 --deploy
Will execute all tasks on all controllers in cluster

Change-Id: I709427ad918c10af3f723abe9f3b759a1dcdac26
Closes-Bug: 1465329

commit_message:
Add parameter 'changes-since' for image-list of v1

Now Glance /images/detail API of v1 supports parameter
'changes-since' to query deleted images. But it's missed
in client. This patch will add the parameter.

Related-Bug: #1432701

Change-Id: Id38e3a78b4b2ef680ea04d35e32beb4b9c8efa00

commit_message:
Execute specified tasks only for particular contoroller

>> fuel node --node 2 --tasks netconfig
Will execute task only on provided node, without additional controllers

But

>> fuel node --node 2 --deploy
Will execute all tasks on all controllers in cluster

Change-Id: I709427ad918c10af3f723abe9f3b759a1dcdac26
Closes-Bug: 1465329

commit_message:
VMware: fix AttributeError: TaskInfo instance has no attribute 'name'

This happens in stable/icehouse with vCenter 6. This is a
stable/icehouse only change since this code was moved to oslo.vmware
and in Juno Nova was using this code from oslo.vwmware.

Furthermore, the _poll_task code in oslo.vmware was taken from cinder
which didn't have the call on task_info.name so the bug isn't there.

Change-Id: I729f1cdca1d4e02e31f26aa0e170c30be1a65288
Closes-bug: #1462424

commit_message:
Add error handling for creating secgroup

If passing invalid value to "create security group" API, Nova passes
it to Neutron and Neutron returns BadRequest response back to Nova.
However, Nova didn't handle the exception.
So this patch adds error handling for the situation.

Change-Id: I11da9ec32b64b5a109d65afe77aa32be71a807a3
Related-Bug: #1460875

[{'created': '2015-06-15 14:43:27.000000000', 'message': "Fix possible usage of undefined variable

In reconnect() the variable is defined after it's being used in
if-section. This could lead to undefined behavior while getting
timeout exception.

Closes-Bug: #1465314

commit_message:
Fix possible usage of undefined variable

In reconnect() the variable is defined after it's being used in
if-section. This could lead to undefined behavior while getting
timeout exception.

Closes-Bug: #1465314

Change-Id: I97720f793728af2158152b7aafcc0ca9a45a6b07

commit_message:
Allow oslo rabbit heartbeat configuration

In order to allow components to better handle and respond to mq failures,
oslo has some heartbeat options that are useful.

Change-Id: Ief96c7fce659376f476b11b527c60ce999777b81
Partial-Bug: #1462438

commit_message:
Switch badges from 'pypip.in' to 'shields.io'

The badge hosting at 'pypip.in' has been broken for a while
now, it was supposed to be fixed in the following PR(s):

- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/39
- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/38
- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/37

That does not appear to have actually happened and/or is not
getting addressed, so switch to a more reliable badge hosting
site that provides the same badge information.

Change-Id: I3d835825973121ed012c382e7c5b0c88d193de87

commit_message:
Replace ssh exec calls with paramiko lib

Nova already has a dependency on paramiko and therefore should
take advantage of it for generating key pairs.  This will reduce
the code complexity and remove calls to exec.

Closes-bug: 1464298

(cherry picked from commit 3f3f9bf22efd2fb209d2a2fe0246f4857cd2d21a)
Change-Id: Ibb01f5227ded9b79816c064a06a1f6724f765e78

commit_message:
Allow oslo rabbit heartbeat configuration

In order to allow components to better handle and respond to mq failures,
oslo has some heartbeat options that are useful.

Change-Id: If21b39cb0c640fea0846f448100842374f97f550
Partial-Bug: #1462438

commit_message:
Allow oslo rabbit heartbeat configuration

In order to allow components to better handle and respond to mq failures,
oslo has some heartbeat options that are useful.

Change-Id: I453b04c90e6caba7c00cf239035af05199bb5c36
Partial-Bug: #1462438

commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fixes this problem.

See this Nova change: If0bc42891a0714cc9b37b9c211388db20555ea7e

Change-Id: I94736408285ad741ff16eab1f9ae9bd30d3f0081

commit_message:
Switch badges from 'pypip.in' to 'shields.io'

The badge hosting at 'pypip.in' has been broken for a while
now, it was supposed to be fixed in the following PR(s):

- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/39
- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/38
- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/37

That does not appear to have actually happened and/or is not
getting addressed, so switch to a more reliable badge hosting
site that provides the same badge information.

Change-Id: Ia1fd048e8f1810c4aaabc24bd01c7f0c18b79fd6

commit_message:
Switch badges from 'pypip.in' to 'shields.io'

The badge hosting at 'pypip.in' has been broken for a while
now, it was supposed to be fixed in the following PR(s):

- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/39
- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/38
- https://github.com/badges/pypipins/issues/37

That does not appear to have actually happened and/or is not
getting addressed, so switch to a more reliable badge hosting
site that provides the same badge information.

Change-Id: Ief3b785ae667c158acef347f3d989bfc23d00267

commit_message:
Fix Enum usage in 589f9237ca0e_cisco_n1kv_ml2_driver_tables

PostgreSQL is more sensitive with types than MySQL, it creates a
separate type when a Enum is created. In migration 589f9237ca0e
type profile_type is trying to be created, but the type with such
name was already created in havana_initial migration.

The solution for this is not to create type in 589f9237ca0e
migration when dialect is PostgreSQL and use already created.

Closes-bug: #1463301

Change-Id: I66e74d50cc70673de8635616076779cc20cde113

commit_message:
hypervisor support matrix: add status "unknown"

When a new feature gets added to the hypervisor support matrix it
was not possible to state that the hypervisor did not make a support
statement yet. You had to choose between "complete", "partial" and
"missing" wich could be missleading.
This change set adds the status "unknown" which could make the
statements more precise.

Change-Id: If94fc772796742de88af5893839945834b9d3eb6

commit_message:
Remove useless 'puppetmaster' module

Fuel deployment scheme doesn't include puppetmaster, so that's
why puppetmaster module could be removed

Partial implements: blueprint upgrade-openstack-puppet-modules

I'm going to rename the file back to bgp-dynamic-routing just for now.  I'd like to see the differences side-by-side."}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-05-07 21:21:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-05-07 21:23:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

Vikram.  I'm trying to wrap my head around the differences between this proposal and Jaume's.  To that end, I rebased yours on to his so that we can see them side-by-side.

Could you help me out by minimizing the differences between the two to what really matters to make the original proposal generic?  If you do that, you may even be able to rename the file back to "dynamic-routing-framework.rst" and gerrit may detect it as a renamed file instead of a delete and add of a new file.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-07 21:28:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-neutron-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/87/180987/6/check/gate-neutron-specs-docs/6a54573//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 21s
- gate-neutron-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/87/180987/6/check/gate-neutron-specs-python27/9cf97d2/ : SUCCESS in 2m 35s'}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-05-08 05:30:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Hi Carl,

I have no issues with the rebasing. I feel it's really a nice idea to check the diff with the existing proposal.

Coming to my changes, I have just updated the existing proposal by adding "type" and "attribute dict wherever required. "type" field will let us know about the protocol type (BGP/OSPF/ISIS) and attribute dictionary will be containing basic configuration required for protocol functioning.

In addition to this I have made some cosmetic changes to make the proposal look generic:)

Thanks
Vikram'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-05-11 00:04:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 14258, 'date': '2015-05-13 17:45:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I'm not convinced the generic dynamic routing framework as outlined here is the right way to go. There is a lot in this such as "speakers" and "peers" that is very BGP-specific. BGP, OSPF, and IS-IS (as examples) operate very differently and have very different configuration parameters. I feel this is the wrong approach. I question whether a generic approach to dynamic routing even makes sense and is feasible, but I'd have to think about it a little more and bounce ideas off others before forming a solid opinion.'}, {'account_id': 14605, 'date': '2015-05-15 07:29:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Ryan: I agree the notion of IGP and BGP is different but there are configuration in IGP's like P2P in OSPF and unicast peer in RIP which can simulate peer communication in unicast mode. Moreover, policy could also control the route advertisement if needed."}, {'account_id': 7505, 'date': '2015-05-18 14:03:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

More than the abstraction of the entities (everything can be abstracted with a dict, right? :) ) 

I am concerned about the api workflow. As far as I know, peer discovery on OSPF is automatic, sending L2 frames between routers. How would you use `routingpeer-create` on OSPF? You just skip this step?

I would like to see more elaboration on this.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-15 15:30:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 7448, 'date': '2015-06-15 16:52:46.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Let's abandon this for now.  If we find we need it later, we can restore."}]

[{'created': '2015-05-07 13:26:13.000000000', 'message': 'Submitting BP for "dynamic-routing-framework"

Change-Id: I1af620769b82bc33001cbcff1cc644922257dc04
'}, {'created': '2015-05-07 13:27:24.000000000', 'message': "Neutron has shown interest in connecting it's internal network via a separate up-link using BGP (https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/bgp-dynamic-routing).The proposal is tightly coupled with BGP and cannot be leveraged by other routing protocols.

This proposal talks about a generic framework for making neutron router/s, network/s, subnet/s and route/s reachable via any of the dynamic protocol like BGP, OSPF, ISIS, OSPFv3, EIGRP and etc.

Change-Id: I1af620769b82bc33001cbcff1cc644922257dc04

Merge puppetlabs/concat 1.2.3

While 2.x has been already released, it will most likely break our
manifests in subtle ways[1]. The fix is scheduled for Puppet 5.0[2].

[1] https://tickets.puppetlabs.com/browse/MODULES-2104
[2] https://tickets.puppetlabs.com/browse/PUP-1963

commit_message:
replaced libraries/database with lwrp

- defined lwrp openstack_common_database
- removed libraries/database.rb
- created _openstack_common_database_spec.rb recipe for testing the
  provider
- comments for db2 in provider since this resource does not exist in any
  availabe or linked opensource cookbook
- updated README.md

commit_message:
improve email format with stable and other tags

Separate the series specification from the stable branch flag so we can
always include a series in release notes subjects.

Add an option to specify other email topic tags to be added to the
beginning of the subject line, so we can add project names for libraries
where the project may not be obvious.

Change-Id: I8dd662c24257346cee76128643b4eee202a89dd7

commit_message:
Change "find" command path in tox.ini

tox command shows WARNING message as follow.
"WARNING:test command found but not installed in testenv"
If we use "find" command in tox.ini, we should use the full path.
This patch changes fix command path and remove the Warning message.

Change-Id: Icb86ff2294ee79e500b98ef79e458f0302dc295e
Closes-bug: 1464495

commit_message:
Add unstable Neutron job

A higher degree on concurrency triggered by patches [1, 2] led to instability
of the full Neutron job. Since it is difficult to troubleshoot and solve instability
issues whilst the gate is crippled, it is better to introduce an ad-hoc unstable job
that let folks work in isolation. Once issues are resolved, this job can be nuked.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/184383/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/140493/

Change-Id: Id406d50f63c433c7b4b1510bb176b280ac470ca0

commit_message:
Removed output sorting in client

The client was sorting based on particular fields which made pagination strange
because we're paginating based on the ID.  We now leave the data in the order
that the API returned it.

Change-Id: Ie62d05d5d55fa29cf2f85b672b530ffa041b3c19

commit_message:
Use indexer RDBMS as tooz coordinators

This modifies the storage class a bit to include a stop() method. We
currently rely on the GC to close the connection, but when the GC is
lazy, the number of connection to the tooz coordinator can become very
high and explode.

Change-Id: Ibdc8f5b5d7191eef948b1e66f05b3a5c696c6079

commit_message:
Skip rescheduling networks if no DHCP agents available

This eliminates the problem of unscheduled networks in case
of communication failure between agents and servers which
can occur if messaging queue service fails.

Change-Id: Ied4fa301fc3d475bee25c47f3a01c2381ae9a01e
Closes-Bug: #1461714

commit_message:
Remove mainly untranslated locales

Remove the following locales since they have too few translations. This
removes only the cached content from this repository, the original
content stays on transifex. Once these documents are better translated
our tools will import them again.

Only one found:
* install-guide:
  - ko_KR.po (684 translated strings out of 1257 - 54 % translated)

This one was not even part of our testing toolchain since it misses
dependencies for building (no common translations).

Change-Id: I2a3738d531f174e0ef5a7c682ccb0ffa6db5f2fd

Remove unnecessary registration of glance resource

This resource was moved from contrib to the main tree and now is not
required to register this resource in tests.

commit_message:
iPXE to use Swift Temporary URLs

This blueprint adds support for generating Swift temporary URLs for the
deploy and image's ramdisk(s) and kernel(s) when booting with iPXE.

This blueprint depends on the blueprint ipxe-dymic-config that makes
the iPXE configuration files to be dynamically generated.

Change-Id: Ibae6e6401fa0458b8ecc74b47a213d587f4974a5

commit_message:
perf tools: remove deprecated API

pandas.datumFrame have been deprecated for pandas.DataFrame a long
time ago. And now don't exists anymore.

This change fixes that.

Change-Id: I7501d1d2bc8f1ac16ffe72195a4925cf8659775d

commit_message:
Use DEVSTACK_GATE_SETTINGS in networking-ovn

Update the networking-ovn tempest job to set DEVSTACK_GATE_SETTINGS
so that the networking-ovn repo can contain a file that sets up a
custom DEVSTACK_GATE_TEMPEST_REGEX.

Change-Id: I43f00d889fc44b7d5a43a60b729bf8e9ada1eb22
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Set permissions on user_secrets.yml to 0600

The permissions on the user_secrets file are too open, adjust this so that
after using pw-token-gen.py it sets the file to be 0600 for
user_secrets.yml and the backup tar file that is created. Additionally,
add a note in the README to recommend adjusting the permissions when not
utilising the pw-token-gen.py

Change-Id: I90ffacd83a89a92f48cf160e5b351e1254e9c73a
Closes-Bug: #1461997

commit_message:
Separate base images into different folders

This moves a few things around. Namely centos/fedora-rdo-base becomes
centos/rdo/base
fedora/rdo/base

I have also separated out RHEL.

Moves the current scripts in "base" to a "common" folder common to all
images and then recreates the appropriate links to allow all the
containers to build the same way they did before.

This removes all .buildconfs in the system (though they are still usable)

Partially Implements: blueprint refactor-base-image-layout

Co-Authored-By: Martin Andr√© <martin.andre@kvhasia.com>
Change-Id: Id63eac1eb9893ceb775c28bf22842dede85c214a

commit_message:
Create Tablename class

Previously, the tablename was really 3 separate
fields: name, service, and modal.  This was confusing
and the logic for implementing the tablename was
spread throughout the codebase.

This change adds a Tablename class to encapulsate
all that functionality

Change-Id: I00e4bad2d8391e66e8b86201e2d283668f50cfc8

commit_message:
Add configuration switches for features that make Neutron unstable

Both using pymysql and multiple api workers unveiled a number of races that
occur when accessing the DB layer. We should enable these features in an
unstable configuration for Neutron so that we can shake them out and go back
to sanity.

Related-bug: #1464612
Related-bug: #1432189

Change-Id: Ib6346d53a1a5d99d868ee3ded0ce112b9d68ab51

More Javelin Unit tests

Improving unit test coverage of javelin2.
Keep on truckin'!

Adds tests covering volumes manipulation:

* Volumes: create/destroy/attach

Change-Id: Ia661db77e3a4c9d75514c4a292112a4979969ecc

Louis, I think it's exactly what is expected:

be it an added/altered/removed command line option, a deprecated or new feature, a caveat, _if you've written docs in the patch_, or if you're just not sure, just add "DocImpact" to a line in your commit message.

commit_message:
Add info how to avoid issues with token expiration

This commit adds strings that describe how to prevent situations
related to the issues with token expiration during big file upload.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Iddc78a8ce32b78aefe5b702d35b30c13935117bf
Co-Authored-By: Mike Fedosin <mfedosin@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Add make_feature_branch.sh

Add a script for creating feature branches.

Move the code for updating the .gitreview file of a branch to a function
that can be reused by make_library_stable_branch.sh and the new
make_feature_branch.sh.

Change-Id: Ic40df4de12380dacb97dd606a30edfdbbe4196a8

commit_message:
kilo: flavor-from-sysmeta-to-blob is implemented

This blueprint was implemented in Kilo and it's
all over the release notes for Kilo regarding upgrade
steps, so let's make sure it sits in the correct category
in the specs page on specs.o.o to avoid confusion.

Change-Id: If24dbcf3ba8c671c80352773aacd3f6a7ec84da2

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-01 23:24:59.000000000', 'message': 'Integrate VP-placement engine with PuLP

Change-Id: Ic298b3b2c9e655cac23b65642a450a3dcc6a3312
'}, {'created': '2015-05-04 23:40:09.000000000', 'message': 'Add conversion of DatalogLp to PureLP

Previously we generated a Datalog-version of a linear program,
but we could find no LP program that would accept that program
as input. In particular, we could find no LP solvers to handle
boolean indicator variables, where the value of the variable
is 1 if and only if some inequality holds.  In the below
example, Y is the indicator variable.

Y := X < 5

This change adds a post-processing step to translation process
of Datalog to LP to ensure that all formulas generated
can be handled by most LP solvers.  That is,
every formula in the output is now of the following form:

ax1 + ... + axn [<=, =, >=] b.

This conversion requires having bounds on the individual variables
that appear in an indicator-variable assignment statement, a
requirement that we found in every explanation of how to
handle binary indicator variables in the literature.

Change-Id: Ic298b3b2c9e655cac23b65642a450a3dcc6a3312

ax1 + ... + axn [<=, =, >=] b.

This conversion requires having bounds on the individual variables
that appear in an indicator-variable assignment statement, a
requirement that we found in every explanation of how to
handle binary indicator variables in the literature.

Also add Ruby's VM-migration code and hook that code up.

Change-Id: Ic298b3b2c9e655cac23b65642a450a3dcc6a3312
"}, {'created': '2015-05-13 20:17:51.000000000', 'message': "Add conversion of DatalogLp to PureLP

Previously we generated a Datalog-version of a linear program,
but we could find no LP program that would accept that program
as input. In particular, we could find no LP solvers to handle
boolean indicator variables, where the value of the variable
is 1 if and only if some inequality holds.  In the below
example, Y is the indicator variable.

Y := X < 5

This change adds a post-processing step to translation process
of Datalog to LP to ensure that all formulas generated
can be handled by most LP solvers.  That is,
every formula in the output is now of the following form:

ax1 + ... + axn [<=, =, >=] b.

This conversion requires having bounds on the individual variables
that appear in an indicator-variable assignment statement, a
requirement that we found in every explanation of how to
handle binary indicator variables in the literature.

Also add Ruby's VM-migration code and hook that code up.

Change-Id: Ic298b3b2c9e655cac23b65642a450a3dcc6a3312

commit_message:
Add Datalog to LP conversion

This change converts Datalog into a PuLP LP program.
The conversion consists of 2 steps: (i) converting Datalog to
an arithmetic constraint language that understands and, or, =, !=,
arithmetic, and variables and (ii) converting that language
into a linear program.

For the use cases we target, the arithmetic constraint
language is semantically the same as a linear program, except that
the constraint language is allowed to include and/or
and boolean indicator variables (like Y = X > 2).
In contrast, in a linear program every formula is of
the form:

ax1 + ... + axn [<=, =, >=] b.

Change-Id: Ic298b3b2c9e655cac23b65642a450a3dcc6a3312

commit_message:
Let the eventhandler manage serial console workers

At the moment, if an instance is unexpectedly power off or paused,
although the serial console worker threads are stopped, there is no
cleanup performed. For example, the serial proxy will still be
accepting connections.

This patch lets the event handler manage serial console workers
based on the recieved events.

Change-Id: I154e5796698dc6a57defb588c5d47f4f095fe7de
(cherry picked from commit ebb9e9d9ad6349319b80786d0f7ca237ed31b3b7)

commit_message:
[stable 6.1]Rename platfrom tests to keep run ordering

Node plagin run tests in adc order,
as result platfrom tests runs before smoke, that is wrong

So  platfrom_test to tests_platfrom
to get smoke tests executedbefore platform

Closes-Bug: #1465238
Change-Id: I91774614afb7edc0ecec3f5b592b75db224ac543

commit_message:
Let the eventhandler manage serial console workers

At the moment, if an instance is unexpectedly power off or paused,
although the serial console worker threads are stopped, there is no
cleanup performed. For example, the serial proxy will still be
accepting connections.

This patch lets the event handler manage serial console workers
based on the recieved events.

Change-Id: I154e5796698dc6a57defb588c5d47f4f095fe7de

commit_message:
Rename platfrom tests to keep run ordering

Node plagin run tests in adc order,
as result platfrom tests runs before smoke, that is wrong

So  platfrom_test to tests_platfrom
to get smoke tests executedbefore platform

Closes-Bug: #1465238
Change-Id: I91774614afb7edc0ecec3f5b592b75db224ac543

'}, {'created': '2015-06-03 14:07:16.000000000', 'message': 'Switch to SwiftService for segmented uploads

Adding a functional test to try to upload files to swift including one
over the default single file size limit of 5GB to test that segmenting
avoids this limit properly. Also because sending 5GB of nulls does take
a while, set a 10 minute timeout and use new feature to ignore timeouts
to make this work in automated jobs that set OS_TEST_TIMEOUT.

commit_message:
Switch to SwiftService for segmented uploads

Swift caps individual file sizes at various levels, so we need to adapt
to this and upload in segments. swiftclient includes the SwiftService
object to do just that.

This adds a functional test to try to upload files to swift.  Because
sending 5GB of nulls does take a while, we're just going to try a
segmented upload and an unsegmented one, and see how that goes.

Note that this test coverage found a missing ObjectDelete task which
has been added. We also add the ObjectCapabilities task so that we can
make sure segment_size is never higher than max_file_size.

Change-Id: I43903235576245a316ae1921505237e9298b5200

commit_message:
Add parent_id information in the Project options

In kilo, Keystone provide the possibility to create a project hierarchy.
Now, in the project operations, you can provide a parent_id to represent the
parent project.

This patch add the parent_id information in the identity API ref.
Updated code samples to use actual values rather than
placeholders like --endpoint-id-- (DF)

Change-Id: Idc22d9f0ff55f161bd0dc5a81974e91018e37b7b

commit_message:
Increase monitor timeout for RabbitMQ OCF

W/o this patch timeout operation may exceeded
its limit making the resource failed and restarted.

This is an issue as we don't want false failures
for the AMQP cluster, therefore less aggressive
timeouts management is required

Closes-bug: #1464131

Change-Id: I35aba8bca68f871b5a794a171011f9933fa38cdd
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Adjust wait to allow erase_node to send response

This change changes the way the erase_node action performs the cleanup
of the disks. We attempt to remount any ext2/3/4 devices as RO and
set the error action to continue. Additionally we are no longer using
sysrq to sync all file systems, reboot all file systems, or sending a
SIGTERM to all processes. Now the disk erase occurs and a sysrq to
reboot the machine after 5 seconds via a forked process. This should
allow for mcollective to send back the response to the fuel node to
acknowledge the erase_node action.

Change-Id: If5ce3d1c2ce99ec422a372bfc30b273583f9fb38
Closes-Bug: 1461074

commit_message:
Add smoke mode for neutron jobs

Add new parameter smoke that allows to run only 1 iteration of
each scenario and avoid any kind of concurrency issues

This patch as well enables it

Change-Id: I9625feb4f2f696a5765b809efcc81dc313e9ce05

commit_message:
Add copytruncate to conntrackd logrotate config

Currently the service restart of conntrackd does not always result
in the log files properly being rotated. We have seen instances where
the file will continue to be written to even after rotation. In order
to address this, this change adds a copytruncate to the logrotation
configuration.

Change-Id: I9832021c88d8dde87e9b391b50b479e81f630402
Closes-Bug: 1464932
Related-Bug: 1461400
(cherry picked from commit e642a55e1485c478f1701a74b9dde4983bdda604)

commit_message:
Remove openstack_extras module

We should avoid adding new forks of upstream modules.
This module was added by Ib607cd77d56e55489e2a855c7ca933b8eb9fcaee
but had yet to be referenced in Fuel, so can be removed safely.

related blueprint pacemaker-improvements
related blueprint merge-openstack-puppet-modules

Change-Id: I533c3bf5aa82fa4d54d28e48b670a52ca3afeedc
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Remove useless 'qpid' puppet module

  Fuel deployment scheme doesn't include QPID
  as amqp service. We are using RabbitMQ.
  That's why qpid puppet module could be removed.

  Partial implements: blueprint upgrade-openstack-puppet-modules

Change-Id: I9766ffb6c2c9c33b8565e52fd55c3e46c78ced3c

The change looks ok, but I would like us to explore an alternative road.

Specifically, can we imagine a reasonable way to automatically detect whether this specific network is vulnerable to the issue (=dhcp agent serving the network runs on a host that manages one of VMs in the same network), and if so, how resource consuming it is. If it's possible and not too consuming to detect those cases, I suggest we do so and automatically enable checksum hack for them, and avoid doing so for other dhcp networks.

This would buy us the following:
- correct behaviour for all types of installation out of the box;
- at the same type, avoiding the hack for non vulnerable setups;
- no new configuration option.

What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 2733, 'date': '2015-01-24 19:41:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hmm that sounds a bit complicated. But how about having neutron.agent.linux.interface.BridgeInterfaceDriver.plug() doing `ethtool -K $TAPNAME tx off` after it creates the device?'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-01-26 09:12:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Darrakh, won't it mean that we will always recalculate checksums and not just for DHCP packets? This does not seem better than existing solution in terms of performance."}, {'account_id': 2733, 'date': '2015-01-26 09:56:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

@Ihar yeah. How about just after the plug() call? - I added a inline comment where.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-01-26 10:01:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Darragh, so as far as I understand ethtool approach enables checksum fill for all packets leaving dhcp namespace, right? This probable applies for DNS traffic, and HTTP in case of isolated metadata. Isn't it a problem even in comparison to iptables approach?"}, {'account_id': 2733, 'date': '2015-01-26 10:15:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Ihar, yeah. I thought the quantity of data involved with DNS and metadata would be very small, but I guess a network node could be serving a lot dhcp clients.

What do you think about the other part of my comment - about having DeviceManager detecting if the linuxbridge driver is in use and applying the iptables rule - this way would mean no need for an option?'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2015-01-26 10:35:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Darragh, quoting Ian from the bug: "And, for what it's worth, there's no reason I know of why this behaviour would differ between LB and OVS." Is it really Linux Bridge specific?'}, {'account_id': 2733, 'date': '2015-01-29 17:09:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Ihar, see the bug report for some testing I did with OVS. There seems to be an issue there too, so maybe it would be best to have this ip rule enabled by default?'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-01-30 20:48:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Always fill UDP checksums in DHCP replies

In some cases the UDP checksums in packets from DHCP servers are
incorrect. This is a problem for some DHCP clients that ignore
packets with bad checksums. This patch inserts an iptables rule
to ensure DHCP servers always send packets with correct checksums.

Change-Id: I130fe0f2389bdc42eb8c858ea35dd840abecc2e7
Closes-Bug: 1244589

commit_message:
Fix functional tests and tox 2.0 errors

With the recent update to tox 2.0.x, environment variables such as
OS_AUTH_URL are not passed by default, resulting in tests errors
mentionning Keystone authentication failures.

This patch reads credentials from the 'functional_creds.conf' config
file, like it is done in novaclient, glanceclient, manilaclient and
soon in cinderclient.

Reading credentials the old way (the environment) is still possible.

Conflicts:
	neutronclient/tests/functional/test_clientlib.py

Change-Id: Ief0f050044ecd90a14bbaf044e2b93ade0a6173f
Closes-Bug: #1455102
(cherry picked from commit 7eb3241650ad87d2f6ca5aa45b3a2415eafe7207)

commit_message:
Unset other authentication options

Add a bunch of unset commands to userrc files. This means that if you
have a bunch or userrc files or are using other authentication files
then sourcing a userrc file reset any existing auth attributes so the
application doesn't get confused.

Change-Id: I78904204f379e8ad103172c0e08627d0181dcd9b

commit_message:
Common Token Model

This is what I want for a common token model. Everything that uses the
token from a client or server perspective should be made to work against
this interface.

Change-Id: I86bd3a2b1bb852ee8d81e368d9f6f28650008892

commit_message:
Fix docstrings for assorted methods

Per review comments the docstring of the inner method 'read_enabled'
is removed and a short comment left in it's stead.

Change-Id: Ie8534a4614326f66f0b014f8f1fad72f9a4db220

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

commit_message:
Add flag DEVSTACK_GATE_NEUTRON and enable heat grenade plugin

devstack-gate expects the DEVSTACK_GATE_NEUTRON flag to be
set in order to create the subnet with the right gateway.

The gate job is also modified to work with the newest external
plugin code in Grenade -> https://review.openstack.org/#/c/185050/

Change-Id: I0f02b00dff6e2c3bf9100292243f2f6e20937d27

commit_message:
Avoid really overlooooooooong lines in RST

We aim to have no lines longer than 79 characters, enable the line
checking niceness check but set it to 100 as current maximum.

Convert files that fail this line length.

Convert one table to a definition list, convert two tables to use
list-table directive.

Change-Id: I8d0a95cc1c8e72965b3e0e69445e7b2bc6d77f0f

commit_message:
Correctly kill nova-network forked dnsmasq processes

Nova-network OCF script tries to stop dnsmasq processes that might be
left after nova-network abnormal termination.  It must do that to
prevent appearence of two gateways and two DHCP servers in VM network.
Right now script stops *all* dnsmasq processes it finds, but this way it
kills dnsmasq processes that serves as upstream DNS server, which is
managed by 'p_dns' pacemaker resource.  Deadlock appears when
'p_vcenter_nova_network' resource tries to stop dnsmasq and 'p_dns'
starts it again.

Lets just find dnsmasq PIDs that were started by nova-network and
terminate them.

Change-Id: I4ec7a60e31a0ce02c1924e6294aa767ad840617d
Closes-bug: #1458821

managed by 'p_dns' pacemaker resource.  Deadlock appears when
'p_vcenter_nova_network' resource tries to stop dnsmasq and 'p_dns'
starts it again.

Lets just find dnsmasq PIDs that were started by nova-network and
terminate them.

Change-Id: I4ec7a60e31a0ce02c1924e6294aa767ad840617d
Closes-bug: #1458821
"}]
commit_message:
Correctly kill nova-network forked dnsmasq processes

Nova-network OCF script tries to stop dnsmasq processes that might be
left after nova-network abnormal termination.  It must do that to
prevent appearence of two gateways and two DHCP servers in VM network.
Right now script stops *all* dnsmasq processes it finds, but this way it
kills dnsmasq processes that serves as upstream DNS server, which is
managed by 'p_dns' pacemaker resource.  Deadlock appears when
'p_vcenter_nova_network' resource tries to stop dnsmasq and 'p_dns'
starts it again.

Lets just find dnsmasq PIDs that were started by nova-network and
terminate them.

Change-Id: I4ec7a60e31a0ce02c1924e6294aa767ad840617d
Closes-bug: #1458821

The upgrade scripts have a *ton* of historical cruft in them. This is
a bulk clean up patch that does the following things:

   devstack dir definitions.

   that we include the minimum possible code in these scripts (for

commit_message:
clean up upgrade scripts

The upgrade scripts have a *ton* of historical cruft in them. This is
a bulk clean up patch that does the following things:

 - ensures we source grenaderc before functions, we need this for
   devstack dir definitions.

 - moves xtraces until after sources to trim down irrelevant output

 - removes as many variables and library sources as possible to ensure
   that we include the minimum possible code in these scripts (for
   sanity and readability).

This skips the neutron upgrade script, much like in devstack, the
neutron code has so many extra variables it's not clear what's really
needed.

Change-Id: Idac9190fd33478a479f7c7dd5cb1be894bb03444
(cherry picked from commit 8ee1af8f3b9fd55a990ff51409623ccd6b80e3e2)

commit_message:
support apache based upgrades for keystone

The following changes are needed for apache based keystone to upgrade

- add lib/apache to keystone shutdown
- don't check for screen logs for keystone after upgrade

Closes-Bug: #1456835

Depends-On: Ic9174f6f959f95eabf76ba8b8a19729898194a61
(devstack-gate change to revert to old correct behavior)

Change-Id: I8bc9d1362df95eba6436bd5f564001fe8b750386
(cherry picked from commit cf655ee07891dcd5abe3b01e2b2f716038aa8792)

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-02 11:59:37.000000000', 'message': 'VPNaaS: Fix breakage in status reporting

In the plugin, the status for the VPN service and its connections
are only updated if there is a change in the status or if the
pending_status_update flag is set. This flag is supposed to be
set when the status changes and the database has the resource in
PENDING_* state.

In the failure case, when the connection is created, the service
and connection are in PENDING_CREATE state in the plugin. In the
device driver, because of the create the service is set to ACTIVE
and its pending_status_update flag is set. The connection will be
in either DOWN or ACTIVE state and the pending_status_update_flag
is set. This is as expected.

When the device driver is about to report, it reads the latest
status and updates it, before reporting. This is where the bug
occurred.

Because of the recent change for translating the FQDN of peer to
IP address, if that fails, it attempts to set the status to ERROR
and force an update by setting updated_pending_status (so that it
updates, even if in pending state). However, the implementation
is set the updated_pending_status flag based on this "force" flag,
which is by default, false.

As a result, the flag gets cleared before the first report is sent
and the connection is never updated from then on (because it never
checks again to see if in PENDING_* state).

the forced flag is set, otherwise leave it alone so that the flag
is not cleared on the first report.

In the future, this shoudl be reworked to a simpler mechanism that
just checks previous vs current status and reports any change, and
the plugin unconditionally updates the status.

commit_message:
VPNaaS: Fix breakage in status reporting

In the plugin, the status for the VPN service and its connections
are only updated if there is a change in the status or if the
pending_status_update flag is set. This flag is supposed to be
set when the status changes and the database has the resource in
PENDING_* state.

In the failure case, when the connection is created, the service
and connection are in PENDING_CREATE state in the plugin. In the
device driver, because of the create the service is set to ACTIVE
and its pending_status_update flag is set. The connection will be
in either DOWN or ACTIVE state and the pending_status_update_flag
is set. This is as expected.

When the device driver is about to report, it reads the latest
status and updates it, before reporting. This is where the bug
occurred.

Because of the recent change for translating the FQDN of peer to
IP address, if that fails, it attempts to set the status to ERROR
and force an update by setting updated_pending_status (so that it
updates, even if in pending state). However, the implementation
is set the updated_pending_status flag based on this "force" flag,
which is by default, false.

As a result, the flag gets cleared before the first report is sent
and the connection is never updated from then on (because it never
checks again to see if in PENDING_* state).

The fix is to simply only update the pending_status_update, when
the forced flag is set, otherwise leave it alone so that the flag
is not cleared on the first report.

In the future, this shoudl be reworked to a simpler mechanism that
just checks previous vs current status and reports any change, and
the plugin unconditionally updates the status.

Change-Id: Id49e54c49f3c72f676b6f2513288c0eae2c6db7b
Closes-Bug: #1440655
(cherry picked from commit 462a1165d8f347ff5afa08aa502436ee7d4dc9dd)

commit_message:
Add copytruncate to conntrackd logrotate config

Currently the service restart of conntrackd does not always result
in the log files properly being rotated. We have seen instances where
the file will continue to be written to even after rotation. In order
to address this, this change adds a copytruncate to the logrotation
configuration.

Change-Id: I9832021c88d8dde87e9b391b50b479e81f630402
Closes-Bug: 1464932
Related-Bug: 1461400

I support this effort, but I don't think we need a spec for this work.

If we do this right, we don't need nova changes. At least thats my hope, please let me know if thats wrong.

We might want a spec to deprecate the EC2 API, but thats different.

For these reasons I am -2ing this spec, but its not because we don't support this effort."}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-01-29 08:25:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I confirm. This stuff is totally independent from nova and doesn't ask for any changes. It did have to make some tradeoffs for this, for example, going directly into novaDB for some stuff which is not exposed via API. So later we might want to add some things to nova or fix some bugs to get rid of those trade-offs. But for now the code doesn't require any changes."}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2015-01-29 08:28:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

If you are going to the Nova DB, are there implications for scaled out implementations (such as using Nova conductor or cells) ?'}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-01-29 09:55:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Tim, right now there might be implications because we go directly to NovaDB by means of mysql connection registered in our config. That's what we found Nova API did when we started, so we just did the same.
However, it's just a couple of places in the code, which we had to put because it was the fastest way to get info reported by legacy nova's EC2 but not exposed by nova via API. 
So it'll be easy to change to any other way of receiving such information like fetching over RPC.
Or we can just switch it completely off basing on configuration flag -those are not the most important pieces of information that would go missing."}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-01-29 10:02:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Tim, from what we know now our main functionality does access to NovaDB the same way as NovaAPI so the scalability shouldn't suffer for this reason. But we also have Metadata service, which if used might be affected. So if you don't use Metadata service you should be safe enough I guess."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-01-29 10:45:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

It is not acceptable for any external service to access the Nova database directly. The database schema is an internal impl detail of Nova for which we provide no backcompatibility guarantees. If there is information the EC2 API requires that is not available in Nova APIs, then the only acceptable approach is to add the necessary APIs to Nova to provide this info.'}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-01-29 11:20:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Daniel, we totally understand this and agree with this. We put this novaDB access as a temporary workaround because there was no other way at the moment. However, as soon as any valid replacement is available we'd be only too glad to switch."}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2015-01-29 18:07:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I was thinking through how we could move to a non-integrated-Nova EC2 solution and was wondering how the migration would take place ? We've got a few thousand VMs currently created using the Nova EC2 API. Will these VMs be manageable via the new interface ?

The other question was on the metadata service. Given that we would be splitting the Nova metadata service from the EC2 one, how would this work for services which would offer both ?"}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-01-29 19:49:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Tim, we've got upgrade script for migration of existing EC2 resources from nova's DB into ours. So yes, everything will stay manageable.
As for the metadata service. At the moment it is already separated from nova metadata service. It's installed as another standalone service. It hooks itself before the nova's one. It gets requests coming from Neutron metadata proxies or from instance directly (in case of nova-network) and handles all of the EC2-specific stuff, while letting the rest of the requests get further through to the original nova metadata service."}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2015-01-29 19:56:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thx. For the metadata service my understanding is that the EC2 metadata service would then receive all of the VM requests for the cloud and forward them on to the nova metadata service. Are there good HA models for this as a failure in this area would, to my understanding, affect all of the cloud (EC2 and non-EC2) ?'}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-01-29 20:09:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Tim, this solution (about the metadata) was employed because having no power to anyhow change nova itself and its services we had to come up with some solution. So at the moment this one was the most sane. However alternatives were considered as well. For example, if existing nova's metadata service were made pluggable than we could've just add our EC2-specifics handler and the model would've been the same. But that requires changes in nova.

As for our current solution - the same HA model can be employed as for current nova's metadata service and two Neutron services which stay in the pipeline before nova's metadata. We're just adding another one alike."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-01-29 21:16:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Alexandre, I agree with Daniel. This service should never directly access nova's database under any circumstances."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-01-29 21:17:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

also long run I don't see why this would need to live in the 'compute program', under the new big tent model this can just live inside of OpenStack as its own thing."}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2015-01-30 07:37:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Given that we don't want direct DB access, is there a document which defines which extensions to Nova would be needed to support this EC2 outside Nova ? These can then be spec'd so the underlying external facing APIs are agreed. I suspect they'd be useful for other cases too."}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-01-30 09:33:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Joe, I agree with both of you totally.
Tim, I'll try to see where to go from here in this aspect and then create something in regard.
The info we lack can be divided to 3 categories:

1. Instance: launch_index, reservation_id. 
(We do not have it only for instances launched via OpenStack, not via EC2 API.)

2. Instance: kernel_id, ramdisk_id, root_device_name, hostname, key_data, user_data.
Instance BDM: delete_on_termination.
(We do not have it because for all of the instances, we do not store it ourselves and it's not accessible from anywhere else)

3. Instance BDM: snapshot_id, volume_id, no_device, source_type, guest_format, virtual_name.
(These additional properties are required for Metadata service only but are also absent anywhere else)

So in order to move on what do we do? 
I see the following options:

1. We write a nova-spec for absent properties and use the NovaDB in the meantime.
2. We write a nova-spec for absent properties and remove NovaDB access in the meantime, thus not returning this info in responses.
3. We write nova-spec and put a flag in config which switches between 1 and 2 behavior (accessing NovaDB and not using it).
4. We store the info ourselves for instances run through our EC2 API and return it for those, for instances run through OpenStack there will be gaps then (or we can again use NovaDB). We can also write a nova-spec for absent properties in this case or leave it to work only with our instances.

There can be actually any combination of the above or something else, like us trying to write our own extension for nova for this info...

Joe, what do you suggest we do now?"}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-01-30 09:39:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

A little mistake:

Key_data and user_data are also required only for Metadata service.

BDM is in fact absent completely for Instance.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-01-30 10:03:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I think there needs to be a spec for adding the necessary features to the Nova API.

I don't have an opinion on when you should remove the direct DB access. I do think that the external service can't be considered production ready until the DB access is removed though. So if you want to keep it in the short term while waiting for new APIs to be finished that's not unreasonable, but I'd make it clear that it is only suitable for proof of concept testing as long as direct DB access exists."}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2015-01-31 00:30:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Using the NovaDB directly at all is bad, you should stop using it as soon as possible. As the goal is to get this service production ready. 

In general most of the mapping data should be stored in the database for this service but we may need to add some information directly into nova like launch_index (If you started more than one instance at the same time, this value indicates the order in which the instance was launched. The value of the first instance launched is). There is no way this service can own that piece of data.

As for how to proceed I think the first step is to go into further detail about the missing info in greater detail

* Migration strategy from nova's EC2 to this
* Who should own which piece of data
  * What needs to be added to nova API (or maybe just not support in EC2 API)
  * What can be owned by this service
* What can be safely removed etc."}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2015-02-05 12:13:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

Please see my inline comments. If we just think architecturally, it makes no sense in 
1. Allowing direct access to Nova DB for this standalone service
2. Store information of EC2 related attributes in Nova and expose it via Nova's API which is only going to be consumed by this service. Nobody is going to want such additions to existing Nova APIs/create new Nova APIs

Also, architecturally it's definitely painful and not the right thing to store mappings of nova DB records and our additional attributes in a separate database of this standalone service and lookup into this database strictly after or strictly before almost every EC2 API call.

The soundest approach would be to have this service reside _inside_ Nova, and we improve it there. It seems like we have already decided to move this EC2 API service out of Nova, and then finding out ways to fix all the shortcomings of this decision. We need to look more fundamentally at which is a better way for the service to exist. 


I'll follow this discussion with a mailing list post..."}, {'account_id': 11224, 'date': '2015-02-05 12:33:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I agree with Rushi -  Architecturally, it's reasonable to move-out of Nova. Here, we are diverting the problem. The current problem is EC2 APIs, code is not maintained, so we should stand for make the EC2 API code robust and clean. That solves the issue."}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-02-05 13:19:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(4 comments)

Rushi, 

I agree with you on 1 and 2. 
We should not go to novaDB and we won't. Only current solution does it to demonstrate that it works in other aspects for this data. We'll be removing it as soon as we have required info returned from nova. One of the showstoppers is absence of reservation_id. We have no means to know it for instances started via nova, for example. 
And I agree that it's not sound to make Nova know about EC2-specific stuff. It shouldn't.

However, I disagree with idea of leaving EC2 inside nova and using its database to store EC2 data. I disagree, because in fact, EC2 API is an umbrella on top of all of the OpenStack services. We used nova, cinder, glance, keystone, neutron. And I'd say that with the implementation of VPC API, EC2 API becomes associated with neutron at least in the same degree as with nova, or maybe even more. Also, as you know there is general functionality like tagging, or filtering and such. 
And even if it's not enough, EC2 API is not the only third-party API which is requested to be supported in OpenStack. We've got GCE-API project on stackforge as well. Do you suggest to add all of those projects and tons of code into nova? How would you manage it later?
I believe loose coupling and separated services and projects with their own core teams is the answer for the long run."}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-02-05 13:31:55.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-05 13:46:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-nova-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/82/147882/5/check/gate-nova-specs-docs/5f95ca3//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 3m 06s
- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/82/147882/5/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/b5ed26f/ : SUCCESS in 2m 18s'}, {'account_id': 5538, 'date': '2015-02-05 13:58:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Ideally, every project should have an EC2 server/controller (so nova has one EC2 API, Cinder has one for Volume operations, etc) and then nova, which will be the main entry-point, will route requests to Cinder say if the request is 'list all volumes for a particular tenant'. It will help us drive tagging and filtering features into the core openstack APIs of Nova, Cinder, etc, and then in to the EC2 API. Similarly with tag-isolation for public resources.

I would say the same is the sanest way for adding more APIs like GCE. The only obstacle I can see is Nova's review traffic problem, but that's something which we can't allow to make architecturally flawed decisions. 

I think I'm worried about we not having the list of Nova APIs which will need modification to remove Nova DB access completely, and when we will have one, discovering that some of them might be difficult to get implemented in nova as there is no use of them other than being consumed by the EC2 standalone service. This I'm saying under the assumption/agreement that maintaining a mapping between EC2 and Nova attributes out-of-nova in the standalone project is bad and we are not going to do that as it has performance and consistency implications.

Please correct me if I'm wrong.."}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-02-05 14:12:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Rushi, I believe that in current workflow and processes of Openstack projects, idea of every project implementing and maintaining a piece for EC2 API and then for GCE API is a no-go.

As for the list of absent info which makes us go into NovaDB. I've added the list in the latest patch. There is nothing criminal which is EC2 specific in this list (unless nova doesn't want to support reservations anymore), and I'm writing a new spec for these omissions even now."}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-02-05 14:52:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-05 15:03:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-nova-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/82/147882/6/check/gate-nova-specs-docs/3286e41//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 3m 15s
- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/82/147882/6/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/beb5dd4/ : SUCCESS in 1m 48s'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-04-10 08:29:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

bit confused about the state of this one now, what is left here that we didn't get done during kilo? Need to move this to the liberty/approved directory now."}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-04-10 12:35:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

John, honestly, I'm myself not sure about the way it should go anymore. Initial decision was to have it as part of nova but since then lots of people reasonably asked if it has to do anything with nova at all, now that it's totally independent...
One of the ideas was to discuss the way forward during design summit.
So at the moment the standalone stackfore/ec2-api project is quite self-contained and doesn't need anything critical from nova (some limitations still exist, though). I think we should talk about in what form and when it can be accepted as a part of OpenStack rather than try to go on with this blueprint making this part of Nova.
Actually the same questions are open for the sister GCE-API review here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/149654/"}, {'account_id': 2271, 'date': '2015-04-20 00:44:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I think this would be a good Liberty summit session, although that isn't my call. I can't see it suggested at https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/liberty-nova-summit-ideas -- Alexandre can you please do that?"}, {'account_id': 9312, 'date': '2015-04-20 11:43:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Sure thing, Michael. Thanx for the idea.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-06-15 11:10:01.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

we discussed this a the summit and agreed a way foward.

An external EC2 API makes sense.

Given the cross service nature, we think the project lives outside of the compute project.

Should you need any more bug fixes or API changes to help your cause, please raise the specs or bugs for those specific changes.

Do keep in touch via the nova project meeting when you need help with anything.

Given this approach, I am going to abandon this spec.'}]

commit_message:
Url for fetching filtered installation_infos added

Json export of filtered installation infos implemented.
Limit, offset, total info added into json exporter output for
group operations.
Usage of DB commit decreased in analytics tests.

Change-Id: Ied35132ce3d194b584c8af40576a61e608862c3e
Closes-Bug: #1458528

This commit changes default behavior of logrotate by enabling compress
and delaycompress. The result is that compression is enabled for all log
files managed by logrotate and rotated logs are compressed only on the next

commit_message:
Make log rotation more bulletproof

- use flock to ensure that only one instance of fuel-logrotate is running
- combine centos and ubuntu versions of fuel-logrotate to a single file
- remove unused versions of fuel-logrotate file
- enable delayed compression in system-wide logrotate.conf to avoid race
  condition between fuel-logrotate and regular logrotate
- enable delaycompress also on master node
- default minsize (30M) and maxsize (100M) in system-wide logrotate.conf
- use file_line for logrotate.conf updates
- use bash to execute fuel-logrotate
- fix path to cron's logrotate script in logrotate-debug

This commit changes default behavior of logrotate by enabling compress
and delaycompress. The result is that compression is enabled for all log
files managed by logrotate and rotated logs are compressed only on the next
rotation. It allows us to resolve rotation cycle that might happen when
both regular logrotate and fuel-logrotate were executed at the same
time, causing both to rotate the same file.

Closes-Bug: 1461400
Doc-Impact: ops guide
Change-Id: I94c497a8916fa6fac87ea2ddc51f6de56ab73f98
Co-Authored-By: Alex Schultz <aschultz@mirantis.com>
(cherry picked from commit dd0eacc4606308c6ef54f86d2d6bf2c224a8c713)

commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fix this problem.

Change-Id: I650019ae86e223d5e9c2d4a5b51b92377f3c471e

commit_message:
Make iptables firewall work with L3 plugin without DVR support

iptables firewall implementation expects 'distributed' attribute
is populated in router_info.router, but this attribute is only
populated when L3 plugin supports DVR extension. This commits
take into account the case where 'distributed' attribute does
not exist in router_info.router.

Change-Id: I2b0c208d74923f9ea0fc35bcea00e11152bbdb3d
Closes-Bug: #1448439
(cherry picked from commit 649fab93cedb6b1c3be57ff57ed4278de2916514)

commit_message:
Add router to resources section of yaml output

network and router are both top-level network
resources and router should be represented in
the yaml file both for clarity and also having
router name exposed in yaml file is useful for
building white list for tempest cleanup.

In addition horizon also lists networks and routers
as top-level network objects. Adding router to the
test account output aligns with this existing pattern.

Change-Id: Iddebba793a978281f698ea10c167dc0a8765d785

commit_message:
Limit psutil to <2.0.0

Icehouse NOTE:
psutil was capped in Juno https://bugs.launchpad.net/glance/+bug/1298039
but Icehouse was left uncapped and it was working until psutil 3.0.0 was
released on 2015-06-13.

As explained in https://bugs.launchpad.net/glance/+bug/1298039/comments/2
...the author left some of the old methods in place as deprecated versions
without actually documenting that, while others he just removed.
... the ones that glance uses are still in place in 2.0.0, although there's no
indication as to when that will change (especially since they no longer appear
in the documentation).

Original Juno commit message:
The psutil package recently released psutil version 2.0.0.  This version
made a significant number of changes that are not backwards-compatible.
We should thus restrict the OpenStack psutil requirement to <2.0.0 until
we can ensure that our code is compatible with the new API and that the
2.0.0 version of psutil has had time to propogate to the various
distros.

Needed by: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/78793/
Change-Id: I63d01235a949cd10ba87d41ad428818daaf9a756
Conflicts:
	global-requirements.txt
(cherry picked from commit e4ed27959684f719352dd750ee9c9f3325ed64b0)

commit_message:
Fix DVR interface delete by port when gateway is set

When removing a DVR interface by port, the subnet_id
passed to delete_csnat_router_interface_ports is None,
and so it deletes all the DVR SNAT ports for the
router.

This patch fixes this issue by passing in the right
subnet_id to the delete_csnat_router_interface_ports.

Change-Id: I026ec18e59703a928c3e8a5a4d19490861d31b2a
Related-Bug: #1443524

commit_message:
Require pymongo>=3.0.2

The release of pymongo 3.0.2 introduced lots of API changes to the point
where it's hard to maintain support for both, releases prior and after
3.0. Therefore, this patch sets 3.0.2 as the minimum required version
for pymongo, since it's the newest and it introduces improvements to the
management of write/read concerns.

Change-Id: I2c3dc464bcd1f9b601ffaed5ccee691b6101fbc7

commit_message:
Document existence of br-tun and br-int in the OVS agent

Question about the use of the two bridges has come up in the past
multiple times, so let's fill the gap in the developer documentation.

A user-facing documentation patch will have to follow up, if we want
to be very thorough.

Change-Id: I6dac0f9bdaf7b3b7bff8745d4103ccc71df61a0a

The WSMAN API changed between 11g and 12g. The BootSourceType attribute
from the DCIM_BootSourceSetting resource is missing on 11g. With this

commit_message:
DRAC: fix set/get boot device for 11g

The WSMAN API changed between 11g and 12g. The BootSourceType attribute
from the DCIM_BootSourceSetting resource is missing on 11g. With this
change, setting boot device will work on 11g/12g/13g hardware.

Change-Id: I1395b7542dfd433f3b7b99a05aa44e19b6fda897
Closes-Bug: #1413949

commit_message:
Fixed error message for negative values of min_disk and min_ram

In case of v1 api if min_disk or min_ram is passed with a negative value
to the image create command, it returns 400 response with error message
formatted to HTML entity.

Eliminated special characters (>=) from error message, so it will not
cause any encoding issues. Also with this change the error message for
v1 api will be identical to v2 api.

Closes-Bug: 1461776
Change-Id: I71a3cc3ed6bf14f3c0273df053667f1cbf99e98f
(cherry picked from commit b7a29b7825799187678953a6052ce784ec285604)

Filip, this is an old one, actually =) I helped Ekaterina a little bit to make the new pic, so I can comment on some of the changes.

In the old one packages were called workflows and were not stored in the database (but on disk, AFAIK). Now this is not true.

Murano conductor is now called murano-engine.

Arrows on the new diagram represent the direction of the data flow, for example to get an application package murano-engine polls murano-api, which gets the the package from database.

Murano-dashboard is implemented as a plugin to horizon, so it is included inside that square.

And we decided to remove ambiguous OpenStack Services, because it actually doesn't matter for murano how heat spawn a new vm, as long as it does =)

If you have any questions or imrovement suggestions about the image ‚Äî feel free to ask."}, {'account_id': 15168, 'date': '2015-06-02 22:31:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Oh! Filip sorry, I've read your second comment before the first one.

I do agree, that we could add some more legend on the diagram.

BTW solid arrows represent mandatory data flow and dashed arrows represent optional data flow/objects, while arrow directions represent the direction of the data flow.

I guess we could change directions of arrows to and from rabbits.

Like: Engine gets messages from API via rabbit, but I think it doesn't put anything back, so that arrows direction may be wrong. While Engine<->Agent communication should be represented with a bi-directional arrow. I guess."}, {'account_id': 14265, 'date': '2015-06-03 08:34:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-04-28 17:34:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

Some minor comments inline.

Thank you for a small, clean, easy to read driver! This is great. I'm sure other reviewers will spot minor issues, but this is much easier code to review than many others.

Are you aware of the 3rd party CI requirements for cinder? If so, it's fine (and a sensible idea) to post a review before getting CI set up, however you won't be merged without working CI. If you aren't aware then please comment to that effect and we can point you in the right direction.

Welcome to Cinder."}, {'account_id': 16062, 'date': '2015-04-28 17:56:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Duncan --

I'm aware of the CI requirement -- I'm working on setting that up in parallel, and just wanted to get the review process under way.

commit_message:
Add cinder volume driver for Blockbridge EPS

This initial commit includes support for the minimum required volume
operations:

- Volume Create/Delete
- Volume Attach/Detach
- Snapshot Create/Delete
- Create Volume from Snapshot
- Get Volume Stats
- Copy Image to Volume
- Copy Volume to Image
- Clone Volume
- Extend Volume

For more details about our storage backend, please see the blueprint.

blueprint blockbridge-eps-driver
Change-Id: I99c95243bec708c6519cb69c4cb68085ad698c83

commit_message:
Add networking-cisco repo to Neutron

According to the procedure defined in [1], this patch proposes Neutron
to embrace networking-cisco within its fold. This project provides
Neutron support for numerous Cisco products.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/doc/source/devref/sub_projects.rst

Depends-On: I81a54cd47d82778b5e83fddfdeb32e30da4689eb

I'm not particularly crazy about making repos we expect to go away, since we don't really have a good repo deletion story. Can the horizon dashboard not just go into the designate repo?"}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-09-08 08:40:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It likely could, but that didn't appear to be the norm :)

When it comes time to merge into Horizon itself, would it not just be a case of moving the repo to the openstack-attic namespace rather than deleting?"}, {'account_id': 6786, 'date': '2014-09-08 08:56:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Monty, due to the policy dashboards going to horizon after project accepted to integrated release.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2014-09-08 15:10:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hm, I think we should discuss this with the horizon team, then.  We are telling projects that incubation is a key time for integrating with other projects.  I would expect merging horizon integration into horizon itself to be a part of that.

Can we get a thread going on the openstack-dev mailing list about this, Kiall?

Thanks!'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-09-08 20:32:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Russell: Absolutely, I'll write up and email to the dev list tomorrow to discuss.

@All - I've asked Theirry to take this off tomorrows TC agenda so it can be discussed on-list first."}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-09-09 12:01:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

ML thread for discussion: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-September/045441.html'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-09-12 12:00:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

At the moment, Horizon only includes integrated projects (during their first integrated cycle). So a separate project makes sense here.'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-09-22 22:26:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I don't see a strong case for making a new repo here, unless you need separate gerrit privileges for it.

It's not an exact comparison, but Ironic did that successfully with the Nova driver (developed in our tree for a cycle, then moved to Nova and left a shim behind so we wouldn't break existing deployers' configs)."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2014-09-24 09:57:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

@Kiall: given the temporary nature of this repository and the difficulty for Gerrit to "forget" about repositories, would it be possible to add the designate dashboards under some subdirectory of openstack/designate until Horizon is ready to include it ?'}, {'account_id': 1, 'date': '2014-09-26 01:04:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think ideally this should be in horizon, secondarily in designate, but if both of those options are technically infeasible, then lets go ahead and create the throwaway repo.

And then work on how not to have to do that again.'}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2014-10-06 17:46:41.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Apologies, I thought I had abandoned this change a week or so ago.

We'll bring this into the Designate tree."}, {'account_id': 741, 'date': '2015-06-06 14:11:03.000000000', 'content': 'Restored

commit_message:
Add openstack/designate-dashboard to the DNS Services project

This repository will be used for the Designate Horizon dashboard which
currently lives in designate's contib/designate-dashboard fodler. Having
it's own repo will make enabling gates, tarball releases, etc significantly
easier.

Change-Id: I475ea283399b77aae4837bdc9d081531455d5ea6
