commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fix this problem.

Change-Id: I24ca2f991832e5a0689c1051b60caf949d8225a1

commit_message:
Remove error handling of list_networks

list_networks() of compute network client is implemented like:
  if name:
      networks = [n for n in body['networks'] if n['label'] == name]
So if the network of the specified name don't exist, the return value
is an empty dict. lib_exc.NotFound never happens.
This patch removes lib_exc.NotFound handling.

Change-Id: I8a48d31b6e9b932729d2156cf08669a1970d0b5b

The configuration become more and more complicated.

IMHO, what we need to do:
0. Remove all the custom configurations, schedules, inlcuding /etc/logrotate.d/*fuel* on the nodes.
1. Create file /etc/logrotate.d/10-fuel.conf on the master node only, that will have patterns only for our fuel logs. Currently it includes other system files, which already covered by other rotation templates from system packages. 

2. Add these directives to /etc/logrotate.conf on all nodes:
dateformat -%Y%m%d-%s
minsize 10M
maxsize 100M

3. mv /etc/cron.daily/logrotate /etc/cron.hourly/

That's it. One hour will be enough. Even for debug mode. Don't need to have two schedules. 

What we can not achieve with the configuration described above?"}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-06-04 01:25:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

So I'm helping Bartlomiej out on this, but many of these questions were discussed as part of bug 1382515.  My understanding is that every 10 minutes is required for scale. Maxsize does not prevent large logfiles from being created, only triggering an early rotation.  We would still need to run it at a more frequent interval than hourly. I will try and address the the various issues as best I can in another patch set to follow."}, {'account_id': 6502, 'date': '2015-06-04 02:45:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I made that wanted on my lab and realized that missed one important detail, so for now some of my comments are invalid, sorry about that.

So briefly my idea is the following:
1. have one bash script for logrotate, protected with flock, that we implemented here.
2. run this script for all log files (I mean /etc/logrotate.conf /etc/logrotate.d/). It might be /usr/bin/fuel-logrotate as right now.
3. delete logrotate script from any /etc/crond.xxx and run it using crontab jobs with an interval that we want.
4. rename /etc/logrotate/fuel.nodaily to just fuel and use it only for the files that doesn't have it own file in logrotate.d
5. in /etc/logrotate.conf specify min/maxsize and compress/delaycompresss for the saving free space on the disk.

I'll create and test examples of config files and provide a link here.

What do you think folk?"}, {'account_id': 6502, 'date': '2015-06-04 02:47:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

I made that wanted on my lab and realized that missed one important detail, so for now some of my comments are invalid, sorry about that.

So briefly my idea is the following: 

1. have one bash script for logrotate, protected with flock, that we implemented here. 

2. run this script for all log files (I mean /etc/logrotate.conf /etc/logrotate.d/). It might be /usr/bin/fuel-logrotate as right now. 

3. delete logrotate script from any /etc/crond.xxx and run it using crontab jobs with an interval that we want. 

4. rename /etc/logrotate/fuel.nodaily to just fuel and use it only for the files that doesn't have it own file in logrotate.d 

5. in /etc/logrotate.conf specify min/maxsize and compress/delaycompresss for the saving free space on the disk.


I'll create and test examples of config files and provide a link here.


What do you think folk?"}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-06-04 02:53:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

For #1, sure makes sense. Working on it.

For #2, I'm not sure we want to rotate *all* files on a per 10 min basis. We know the fuel ones are the likely ones to run into issues.

For #3, similar to 2 as we only really want our fuel files rotated more often.

For #4, goes with the previous one of we don't necessarily want to rotate all files every 10 mins or whatever interval we pick.

For #5, Sounds reasonable so I'm working on it at the moment using the values from the previous bug.

With these in mind, I should have an update shortly to address #1 and #5. #2,#3 and #4 probably need additional flushing out and experimentation if we want to go that direction."}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-06-04 03:41:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-04 03:41:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

And what will happen in this situation?'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-06-05 01:13:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Yes it is possible for the fuel-logrotate and the daily logrotate may run at the same time.  This would happen if the run at 3am for fuel-logrotate ran longer than 16 minutes (see below).  From a logrotate standpoint, the logrotate.status file is the only logrotate component that would be shared between the two runs.  There could possibly be rotation contention on any files that are duplicated between the normal logrotate config and the fuel specific configuration.  In a first look, nginx is the only log files that are duplicated between the two configurations. There is a small possibility of a double rotation of the nginx logs.



Jun  4 03:00:01 nailgun CROND[28521]: (root) CMD (/usr/bin/fuel-logrotate)
Jun  4 03:16:01 nailgun run-parts(/etc/cron.daily)[28948]: starting logrotate
Jun  4 03:16:01 nailgun run-parts(/etc/cron.daily)[28981]: finished logrotate

The problem with conntrackd is still here. It happens because postscript in logrotate.d/conntrackd doesn't work for some reason, so for the fix this issue we have a couple of ways:

1. add copytruncate in /etc/logrotate.d/conntrackd

2. add copytruncate in /etc/logrotate.conf 

Honestly, copytruncate is a some kind workaround for the deamons, that can't be restarted correctly, on the other hand with this option some messages might be lost(http://linux.die.net/man/8/logrotate). Since a lot of processes has this problem and we already use this option in fuel.nodaily I think we can choose #2 way. It is more safely, because it will be used for all logs and we can avoid the same problems with any other processes."}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2015-06-13 23:27:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

"}, {'created': '2015-06-03 10:04:33.000000000', 'message': "Make log rotation more bulletproof

- use flock to ensure that only one instance of fuel-logrotate is running
- enable delayed compression in system-wide logrotate.conf to avoid race
  condition between fuel-logrotate and regular logrotate
- enable delaycompress also on master node
- use bash to execute fuel-logrotate
- fix path to cron's logrotate script in logrotate-debug

This commit changes default behavior of logrotate by enabling compress
and delaycompress. The result is that compression is enabled for all log
files managed by logrotate and rotated logs are compressed only on the next
rotation. It allows us to resolve rotation cycle that might happen when
both regular logrotate and fuel-logrotate were executed at the same
time, causing both to rotate the same file.

Closes-Bug: 1461400
Doc-Impact: ops guide
Change-Id: I94c497a8916fa6fac87ea2ddc51f6de56ab73f98

commit_message:
Make log rotation more bulletproof

- use flock to ensure that only one instance of fuel-logrotate is running
- combine centos and ubuntu versions of fuel-logrotate to a single file
- remove unused versions of fuel-logrotate file
- enable delayed compression in system-wide logrotate.conf to avoid race
  condition between fuel-logrotate and regular logrotate
- enable delaycompress also on master node
- default minsize (30M) and maxsize (100M) in system-wide logrotate.conf
- use file_line for logrotate.conf updates
- use bash to execute fuel-logrotate
- fix path to cron's logrotate script in logrotate-debug

This commit changes default behavior of logrotate by enabling compress
and delaycompress. The result is that compression is enabled for all log
files managed by logrotate and rotated logs are compressed only on the next
rotation. It allows us to resolve rotation cycle that might happen when
both regular logrotate and fuel-logrotate were executed at the same
time, causing both to rotate the same file.

Closes-Bug: 1461400
Doc-Impact: ops guide
Change-Id: I94c497a8916fa6fac87ea2ddc51f6de56ab73f98
Co-Authored-By: Alex Schultz <aschultz@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Consolidates scheduler utils tests into a single file.

Two separate test files [nova/tests/unit/scheduler/test_filters_utils.py] and
[nova/tests/unit/scheduler/filters/test_utils.py] appear to be testing methods
from the same module nova.scheduler.filters.utils in a very similar fashion.

Additional cleanup:
* Removed superfluous directory [nova/tests/unit/functional]

Change-Id: I4ac41cea3ab3d95a11aca80a469aca516bf44e52
Closes-Bug: #1463918

commit_message:
Merge V2 and V2.1 hypervisor functional tests

Currently v2 and v2.1 have separate functional tests and their
corresponding sample files. As v2 and v2.1 are supposed to be identical,
there is overhead to maintain two set of functional tests and sample files.
We can have one set of tests which can run for both v2 and v2.1.

This commit merges hypervisor functional tests.
Also adding test for hypervisor servers.

In V2 hypervsior API has following extensions
- os-extended-hypervisors
- os-hypervisor-status
In V2.1 above extensions have been merged together in hypervisor plugins

Change-Id: I5ddf3c54dd80a67f71762769d6130db41e772b01

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to compute clients(l*)

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to compute clients which name is "limits".

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Ibe30d01057936cea68f38984064dff107cdcbe5c

I doubt rabbitmq-server startup sequence uses PAM.

sys V init script does:

 RABBITMQ_PID_FILE=$PID_FILE start-stop-daemon --quiet \
            --chuid rabbitmq --start --exec $DAEMON \
            --pidfile "$RABBITMQ_PID_FILE" --background

However start-stop-daemon does NOT use PAM, all it does is just a plain setuid/setgid [1]. Therefore setting resource limits via PAM is useless and won't solve the problem. Perhaps we need to use something like chpst [2] instead.


[1] https://anonscm.debian.org/cgit/dpkg/dpkg.git/tree/utils/start-stop-daemon.c#n1952)
[2] http://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/gutsy/man8/chpst.8.html'}, {'account_id': 12559, 'date': '2015-05-19 08:59:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

1.This patch needs to pass limits into rabbit ocf script. As we have limits for rabbit user configured in limits.d directory,limits will be passed into ocf script automatically,cause we have special wrapper to start all rabbit services as rabbit user.

https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-library/blob/master/deployment/puppet/cluster/files/ocf/rabbitmq#L212-L227

2. In case of rabbit init script we are passing limits into the rabbit init script using direct call:
"[ -f /etc/default/${NAME} ] && . /etc/default/${NAME} "

'/etc/default/rabbitmq-server' is delivering with rabbitmq package.

Only one improvement what i see there it's to configure the same limits in '/etc/default/rabbitmq-server' and '../limits.d/rabbitmq-server.conf' configuration files.'}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-05-19 09:03:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Alexei, we don't use a daemon to start rabbitmq. OCF is responsible for that and it uses su[1] to spawn rabbitmq instance under appropriate user.

[1] https://github.com/stackforge/fuel-library/blob/master/deployment/puppet/cluster/files/ocf/rabbitmq#L212

Furthermore I can easily prove that limits are applied just fine:

root@node-1:~# grep open /proc/7618/limits 
Max open files            80000                112640               file"}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-05-19 09:20:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Good catch Viacheslav, I'll submit updated patch soon."}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-05-19 09:27:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Code-Review

Please improve the commit message (like "ensure rabbitmq resource limits are propagated to ocf script")'}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-05-19 11:11:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 14774, 'date': '2015-05-19 11:11:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Build Started  (1/2) CentOS'}, {'account_id': 14774, 'date': '2015-05-19 11:11:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Build Failed 

http://tpi-logs.mirantis.com/review.vsphere/183787/7/CentOS : FAILURE

http://tpi-logs.mirantis.com/review.vsphere/183787/7/Ubuntu : FAILURE'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-05-19 11:28:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-05-19 11:41:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 11090, 'date': '2015-05-19 14:49:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

Why do we need to pass to rabbit user? We apply limits to process instead in OCF script.'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-05-19 15:08:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(1 comment)

Sergii, could you please reply in inline comments?'}, {'account_id': 11090, 'date': '2015-05-19 15:40:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-2

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-05-20 04:43:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

> Why do we need to pass to rabbit user? We apply limits to process instead in OCF script.

su resets the resource limits:

 ~# ulimit -a | grep 'open files'
 open files                      (-n) 8192
 ~# su -s /bin/bash -c 'ulimit -a |grep "open files"' nobody
 open files                      (-n) 1024'}, {'account_id': 6926, 'date': '2015-05-20 09:18:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

@Alexey, we apply limits to process pid - are you sure su can impact this?'}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-05-20 14:49:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Bogdan,

su resets resource limits (either to values defined via pam_limits or to generic "good enough" ones):

 # ulimit -n
 8192
 # strace -e setrlimit su -s /bin/bash -c 'ulimit -a | grep "open files"' nobody
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_CPU, {rlim_cur=RLIM_INFINITY, rlim_max=RLIM_INFINITY}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_FSIZE, {rlim_cur=RLIM_INFINITY, rlim_max=RLIM_INFINITY}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_DATA, {rlim_cur=524288*1024, rlim_max=524288*1024}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_STACK, {rlim_cur=8192*1024, rlim_max=16384*1024}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_CORE, {rlim_cur=0, rlim_max=0}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_RSS, {rlim_cur=524288*1024, rlim_max=524288*1024}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_NPROC, {rlim_cur=512, rlim_max=512}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_NOFILE, {rlim_cur=1024, rlim_max=4*1024}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_MEMLOCK, {rlim_cur=64*1024, rlim_max=64*1024}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_AS, {rlim_cur=524288*1024, rlim_max=524288*1024}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_LOCKS, {rlim_cur=RLIM_INFINITY, rlim_max=RLIM_INFINITY}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_SIGPENDING, {rlim_cur=22604, rlim_max=22604}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_MSGQUEUE, {rlim_cur=800*1024, rlim_max=800*1024}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_NICE, {rlim_cur=0, rlim_max=0}) = 0
 setrlimit(RLIMIT_RTPRIO, {rlim_cur=0, rlim_max=0}) = 0

commit_message:
Ensure limits are applied to OCF-managed rabbitmq

Currently limits are applied only for root user, but they are not passed
on rabbitmq user (under which processes are being run)

As Debian-based distributions do not enforce limits by using
pam_limits.so by default, we also need to configure it to do so.

Change-Id: I2dd5639ba33ca7185665348ded10ed5b05228a33
Closes-Bug: 1455755

commit_message:
Add a base FC target driver

We're moving towards decoupling transport layer from the
device driver.  One of the pieces outstanding has been
fibre channel, this patch adds a base FC target driver.

The new model could still be easily used, but you have to
stub out a bunch of unnecessary methods from the base class
the base target driver was built with iscsi in mind and a bunch
of abc tags were added to methods that don't apply to FC. Rather
than having every driver that chooses to do FC stub these out
themselves (which defeats the purpose anyway), this adds a simple
non-implemented sub-class that does it for you and abc's only the
two required FC methods.

There's certainly more that can be done here, but for now we just
want to provide a dumb stub to promote use of the new design.

Change-Id: I902a106c514d834033a40cfb9e5b495c46d8dc38

commit_message:
Apply a naming rule of GET to compute clients(h*)

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s"
or "show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the rule
to compute clients which names are "h*".

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Id2346a6c65cd931b8876d6597fbb82361d1f5839

- make ceilometer resources to accept signals? and use python-heatclient from inside VM to signal the metrics to\xa0

commit_message:
Remove heat-api-cloudwatch

Cloudwatch has been already deprecated in Havana[1][2]; Ceilometer should be
used instead.

[1] https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Heat/Using-CloudWatch
[2] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/061834.html

Change-Id: I56122d8d534d809f5371a517de2e94a7cf50dfff
Closes-Bug: 1448201

commit_message:
Use top-level ServiceNetMap for RedisVirtualIP

This change moves the RedisVirtualIP to be in line with how we
now define the rest of the VirtualIPs.  The ServiceNetMap was made
into a top-level parameter, and the assignment of virtual IPs is
based on a lookup of ServiceNetMap. This change also removes the
parameter_default for RedisVirtualIP from the
environments/puppet-pacemaker.yaml file. Since the RedisVirtualIP
parameter is not used in the non-puppet deployment, this change
removes it from controller.yaml. Finally, since the vip is already
created, we remove the vip creation in
overcloud_controller_pacemaker.pp and references to it.

Change-Id: Id955d930c1723a15732968dd71fe30da8b103af4

Well, Tempest is now branchless and will not work in old style.

- Tempest is branchless now onward and going to run against all supported branch. Means- tempest will not have any JUNO branch and onwards branch. Master branch only will be runnable on Ice-House, JUNO, K release of testable projects.

So here also, same tempest CLI tests is going to run on JUNO and K release of pythonheastclient.
  
- If you are going to add test for new CLIs (which are not present in old pythonclient version) then, that CLI tests needs to be added with requirement of client version.
 
- Spec to support new CLI tests are already approved. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/99984/

commit_message:
Tempest test changes for heat-cli change

Changes to 'SimpleReadOnlyHeatClientTest' to reflect
heat cli changes for 'resource-type-template'.

python-heatclient has deprecated 'resource-template' cli command
as it is misleading and provides the template snippet for
resource_type and not resource.

'resource-type-template' is available from 'python-heatclient v0.2.11'

Change-Id: Ib6469caee983454e8f3b8ccbb6fb0f55a8f76878

commit_message:
Update sqlalchemy-migrate to 0.9.6

Nova code change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/153123/ makes the db migrate
operation fail with db2. Need to update sqlalchemy-migrate to 0.9.6 to solve
this problem.

Change-Id: I44ed42cb1d4074581f15e6b5dbea40514e8bfe1b
Related-Bug: 1428477

Add CLI Tests for Marconi

This patch adds the basic config options to add CLI tests for
Marconi.

commit_message:
Add basic read only tests for trove cli

Adds some basic tests for trove CLI interface similar to nova.
It can be used as a placeholder to add more cli tests.

Partially implements blueprint: cli-tests-coverage
Change-Id: I451e3f73a24511ee7506a236915d6242e3d27624

commit_message:
Added missing ceilometer CLI tests

This patch adds following missing Ceilometer CLI tests -
1. help
2. bash completion

In addition to this following optional arguments are also verified.
1. --debug

It also modifies existing code to check outputs of different tests.

Partially implements: blueprint cli-tests-coverage

Change-Id: If4f3094c626311b5fb84c71526a5941aff652d66

commit_message:
Properly handle Service Provider in token fixtures

``keystoneauth.fixtures.V3Token`` doesn't handle service_providers
properly. This attribute is not marked as part of the dictionary, rather
an attribute of the class. In effect, serializied objects didn't include
``service_providers`` correctly. This patch fixes that.

Change-Id: Ie5282c02886c2f8b00114f91abf098bd722cae38
Closes-Bug: #1463473

commit_message:
Fetch Service Providers urls from auth plugins

``base.BaseIdentityPlugin`` class should have methods for easy access to
Service Provider attribues like ``sp_url`` and ``sp_auth_url``.

This patch adds methods:

``auth.base.BaseIdentityPlugin.get_sp_auth_url()``
``auth.base.BaseIdentityPlugin.get_sp_url()``
``auth.identity.base.BaseIdentityPlugin.get_sp_auth_url()``
``auth.identity.base.BaseIdentityPlugin.get_sp_url()``

Change-Id: I06409d82b0b01e9a933667260b5688bd8e31374e
Implements: bp k2k-auth-plugin

I just tried this out for uefi localboot, the system doesn't reboot after deployment :(  Will try to debug more."}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-06-01 07:25:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

(3 comments)

+1 - it worked for me and fixed the problem. I can confirm that the uefi localboot scenario which crashed with hard reboot, works properly with soft reboot.

Why it didn't work for me first time is because I used fedora based IPA ramdisk and sysrq functions aren't enabled in them - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/187111/1.  Raised a patch for that.  So this change if we do should depend on the above patch.

Some comments inline.

Also I hit issue that Jim mentioned when sysrq functions were not enabled (and reboot didn't work) - the ramdisk just kept on heartbeating and instance was marked as active.  I think we need to make sure it doesn't happen.

So, as we have discussed before, we can change the logic to:

1. Add a new command in agent for power off.
2. Execute power_off command in agent, wait for x seconds for the machine to power off and polling the power status every y seconds.
3. If it doesn't power off, do a hard power off
4. Power on the bare metal

The above should work for VMs as well."}, {'account_id': 9315, 'date': '2015-06-09 06:49:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-09 07:25:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

For IPA we currently do a hard reboot at the end of the deployment,
but that doesn't always play nice with some systems specially when they
have to deal with UEFI. So this patch is changing the code in Ironic to
actually tell the ramdisk to reboot itself instead of powering off a
machine after the deployment is done, this will give the kernel the
necessary time to finish sync'ing up whatever it has to sync before
rebooting the node.

This code also continue to do a hard reboot in case the driver is
SSH (VMs) and local boot is enabled. The reason for that is because
after setting the boot device to the VM (from network to disk) the
changes only gets applied after powering off and on the VM.

commit_message:
IPA: Do a soft power off at the end of deployment

For IPA we currently do a hard reboot at the end of the deployment,
but that doesn't always play nice with some systems specially when they
have to deal with UEFI. So this patch is changing the code in Ironic to
actually tell the ramdisk to power off itself instead of hard powering
off the machine from BMC.  This will give the kernel the necessary
time to finish sync'ing up whatever it has to sync before rebooting
the node.

Depends-On: I2a5f984af26bbbe03002bb8c367c8c6af8d91434
Co-Authored-By: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1451310
Change-Id: I831d8dc1d15c82a0caab94173c2b9f147017500f

commit_message:
Apply other "get" rule of GET to image v2 client

[GET /resources] methods should be "list_<resource name>s" or
"show_<resource name>", so this patch applies the part of the
rule to image client.

NOTE: This patch renames get_image_file to load_image_file
because the method gets the content of file. So show_image_file
didn't fit to its meaning. In addition, this renames store_image
to store_image_file for consistency.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I2b354ff7192bea20339c61bedcd2f11eee455381

commit_message:
VMware: Log should use uuid instead of name

The data content of instance.name is assigned
to key "UUID", which is not correct. Since instance name
can be same to more than one instances, we should use
instance.uuid.

Change-Id: I96a02fefd21eeb7f5d7be7fa11f690ae3e7163bc
Closes-Bug:1456872

commit_message:
Improve StackValidationFailed resp param_groups

Use StackValidationFailed exception's parameters
error and path in parameter groups validation for
fuller error message: which error has been raised,
where this error has been raised and why.
This patch relies on topic [1].

[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:merged+project:openstack/heat+branch:master+topic:improve-validation-error,n,z

commit_message:
Check for 'removed' in port_info before reference

scan_ports can return early on no changes, in which case
'removed' won't be present in the dict. The deleted_ports
logic wasn't setup to handle that.

This patch checks for the key before trying to reference it.

Change-Id: I0e2c6d76515ad8e2a2addc8d40451ac003a150f7
Closes-Bug: #1461325
(cherry picked from commit 75f3aaa4cc42c2c1280f6c578e27e64cff8f860c)

commit_message:
Bumping CinderClient to 1.2.2

This is to allow glance_store unit tests to work again. CinderClient's
outdated requirements was creating a version conflict.

Closes-Bug: #1462276
Change-Id: Iaae48d41a62d1c4f74b2aee01864216c787f02fa

commit_message:
Remove suds package from global-requirements

projects have moved to suds-jurko as that one is python3
compatible and is maintained. So let's get rid of suds.

We don't, as a general rule, cap the upper bounds of libraries in master. We *want* to be testing with new releases, to find issues before we release code into the wild.

We do make exceptions in cases where upstream packages are known to be problematic. Is that the case here?"}, {'account_id': 7764, 'date': '2015-03-17 11:26:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Doug In my push to get PyKMIP ready for 0.3.0 and Kilo, I broke backwards compatibility for certain internal library objects and methods; some of the changes were necessary, some were not. When I updated PyKMIP over the weekend, the Barbican gate began pulling in the new version, since the version scope was unbounded. This broke the gate (for about 12 hours) until an emergency patch could be pushed through.

The upper bound is a hedge to make sure we can do sufficient interoperability testing before automatically moving to a new library version and/or new interface.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-03-17 11:30:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

I would agree, this kind of master capping ends up just creating worse issues down the road.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-03-17 11:33:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

@Peter - I understood what you were doing, although I didn't realize you (or we?) managed the library. My point was that we specifically have a policy against capping libraries unnecessarily, and especially if we have control over the code.

Having things be broken once in a while is just part of the development cycle. In the case of upstream libraries, it helps us identify incompatibilities in the way we're using code or persistently problematic upstream developers. I don't think either of those describes this library so I don't think we need the cap."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-17 12:12:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

commit_message:
Update PyKMIP version in requirements

Bump the PyKMIP library requirement to version 0.3.1, which adds
support for creating, registering, and retrieving asymmetric keys.
This is needed for asymmetric key features being added to Barbican.

See the following reviews for more information:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/160449/
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/163989/

Change-Id: Ib951f936bf2a72ce2e5f38c3ef3aa51de9c75230

recheck hgst

Because there is a difference in units between Cinder requests and HGST Space volumes (Gi vs. G) snapshots were not always copying all data at the very end.  Most tests would pass, but when a volume had data in the no-mans-land it would be replaced with 0s in the snapshot.  This patch now only cares about the actual size of spaces including over-allocation, fixing this issue.

Also moving CI system from silent->check after consulting w/rasselin.  Will monitor it over the weekend to ensure no spamming.'}, {'account_id': 15903, 'date': '2015-06-06 05:33:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Dictionary style fix as noted by Apoorva.

Minor tweak to the handling of "blocked" operations to properly identify errors vs. non-errors:

When a command is executed but gets "blocked" and isn't complete when the cli returns, we attempt to kill it.  However if between the time we get notification that it's "blocked" and when we try and kill it, it completed, then this is NOT an error and doesn't need any special notice to the operator or logs.  If we do succeed in cancelling, this is an error because the original command (create a volume/etc.) could not complete, and will be logged as such.

HGST Solutions CI automated run output already added.'}, {'account_id': 14377, 'date': '2015-06-08 03:13:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

Mostly new and better unit tests, with one tweak to the exceptional "blocked" case handling found by them.

Added mocks() for the os.* and socket.* calls used just in case there are servers somewhere running where the user "root" or hostname "localhost" do not resolve.

One corner-case bug fixed:  In the "command-blocked" path I threw an error in a try: block, meaning to send it out to the caller.  Instead it was caught by the except: portion, d'oh.

CI system still seems to be reporting properly, and added cluster diagnostics to the output for our internal debugging goodness.

Otherwise, hope you all have time to give it a look for possible submission to L-1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-09 22:59:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Verified+1

[{'created': '2015-05-28 22:13:51.000000000', 'message': 'Implement Cinder Volume driver for HGST Solutions

Enables native support for HGST Solutions software Spaces as
Cinder volumes or snapshots.

HGST Solutions is a software-SAN-like package which allows local
SSDs in a cluster to be combined into a single storage pool.  This
pool can then be carved into HA (mirror-replicated) "Spaces" which
can be managed/accessed from any member of the cluster.

Each Cinder Volume or Snapshot is mapped to a single HGST Space.
This space may be named differently from the actual volume/snap ID
and so we store the Space Name<->ID mapping in the Cinder metadata.
Snapshots are not supported with the current HGST Solutions
software, so they are implemented as heavyweight copies in the
driver.

All Spaces are made visible on the Cinder host for speed of access,
and only the spaces requested by Nova instances are actually made
visible on other members of the cluster.

Not all nodes need SSD storage to take advantage of these volumes,
cinder.conf entries specify which nodes share their local SSDs.

Prerequisites:
The driver has a series of configuration options which must be set
in the cinder.conf, prefixed with hgst_*.
Nodes should have the software installed and connected to the
HGST domain prior to rolling out Nova nodes using this storage.

Change-Id: Ie0ff03856edd4b5610f4412951ea7c970ad63c8c
Implements: bp/add-volume-driver-hgst-solutions

commit_message:
Implement Cinder Volume driver for HGST Solutions

Enables native support for HGST Solutions software Spaces as
Cinder volumes or snapshots.

Each Cinder Volume or Snapshot is mapped to a single HGST Space.
This space may be named differently from the actual volume/snap ID
and so we store the Space Name<->ID mapping in the volume provider_id.
Snapshots are not supported with the current HGST Solutions
software, so they are implemented as heavyweight copies in the
driver.

All Spaces are made visible on the Cinder host for speed of access,
and only the spaces requested by Nova instances are actually made
visible on other members of the cluster.

Not all nodes need SSD storage to take advantage of these volumes,
cinder.conf entries specify which nodes share their local SSDs.

Prerequisites:
HGST Solutions is a software-SAN-like package which allows local
SSDs in a cluster to be combined into a single storage pool.
The driver has a series of configuration options which must be set
in the cinder.conf, prefixed with hgst_*.
Nodes should have the HGST software installed and connected to the
HGST domain prior to rolling out Nova nodes using this storage.

Additional patches required for full functionality (being tracked
under the same blueprint):
OS-brick patch @ https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186588/
Nova patch @ https://review.openstack.org/#/c/186594/
Nova patch required until os-brick<->nova connection finalized
in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/175569/

Change-Id: Ie0ff03856edd4b5610f4412951ea7c970ad63c8c
Implements: blueprint add-volume-driver-hgst-solutions

commit_message:
Subscribe new oslo projects to g-r process

In liberty the oslo team is starting a bunch of new
libraries
debtcollector
futurist
oslo.service
oslo.cache
oslo.reports
automaton

Adding these to projects.txt will ensure they get the
sync to any new changes in global-requirements

Change-Id: I4ed7acbb839150e37e03140f72f103f8be88767d

commit_message:
Bump fasteners up to 0.7

More code moved out of taskflow to this library so that
others can use it so taskflow would like to use the newer
version (so that it can remove its own version of that
code that is no longer needed inside of it).

Change-Id: I442249783da4a6ae10c78b95e0b279409c95d2e6

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-23 04:27:20.000000000', 'message': "Change ironic ephemeral partition from vda to sda

The metadata ephemeral0 which is used by cloud-init is
set '/dev/sda1' in nova/virt/ironic/driver.py by default.

    if flavor.ephemeral_gb:
        instance.default_ephemeral_device = '/dev/sda1'
        instance.save()

So the ephemeral partition should also be changed from 'vda'
to 'sda'.

Change-Id: I327b51c854cc6be23ade3dce70fb40fa3aea25a5
"}, {'created': '2015-03-23 08:57:50.000000000', 'message': "Change ironic ephemeral partition from vda to sda

The metadata ephemeral0 which is used by cloud-init is
set '/dev/sda1' in nova/virt/ironic/driver.py by default.

    if flavor.ephemeral_gb:
        instance.default_ephemeral_device = '/dev/sda1'
        instance.save()

So the ephemeral partition should also be changed from 'vda'
to 'sda'.

commit_message:
Change ironic ephemeral partition from vda to sda

The metadata ephemeral0 which is used by cloud-init is
set '/dev/sda1' in nova/virt/ironic/driver.py by default.

    if flavor.ephemeral_gb:
        instance.default_ephemeral_device = '/dev/sda1'
        instance.save()

So the ephemeral partition should also be changed from 'vda'
to 'sda'.

Change-Id: I327b51c854cc6be23ade3dce70fb40fa3aea25a5

[{'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-03-27 11:10:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-27 11:19:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/98/168298/1/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/ff2ea3b//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 46s'}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-03-27 11:22:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-27 11:28:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/98/168298/2/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/19a405f//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 49s'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2015-03-27 12:21:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

The current design for SoftwareConfig/SoftwareDeployment was made in a way that allows for tracking the state of each config's deployment thru the resource state of the corresponding SoftwareDeployment resource. If one deployment refers to multiple configs, this will not be possible any more. Also, the ability to define dependencies on the deployment of one config will be lost, the ability to cleanly provide inputs and outputs for one config ...

All that said, I remain to be convinced that this is a good feature."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2015-03-27 19:10:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

While I think that you don't lose the ability to do anything you can do today with this change (this doesn't preclude one-deployment-one-config if that level of tracking and dependency is important), The complexity this would add to input and output mapping seems at first blush pretty hairy, so I'm not convinced either that it would be helpful."}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-03-30 09:00:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thomas Spatzier? Randall Burt

Thank you for reviewing this spec.
As Randall said this change will almost give no influences to the existing one-config-one-deployment feature, you can still check the state of each config during CREATE, and to each config you can also define deployment dependency, and the inputs for each configs can be separated. If you want to use one-config-one-deployment you can just change the Deployment config type to LIST, others are no need to change.
And about inputs and outputs, you can get the same results before and after this change.

As there is no harm to the current feature, and we can trigger many configs by one deployment instead of writing many duplicated deployments, I think this feature is useful.'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2015-03-30 14:46:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I get that if the proposed list of configs would just contain one entry, everything would be as it is today. But I am still not convinced of the usefulness of the new feature, since it has too many drawbacks when we look at the details.

Also, I think keeping the name 'config' but now making it a list is bad user experience, because then it should be called 'configs' (plural). If we changed the name, this would be a break of backwards compatibility. So this should be either a complete new property or even a new resource type."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-03-31 02:36:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

IMO, it would be appropriate to have something like 'multipart mime', which can encapsulate multiple configs and also allow for signalling."}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-04-24 01:22:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Thomas Spatzier

Like your opinion, what about keeping the current 'config' property and add a new property configs, which is a list type?"}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-04-24 01:30:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-24 01:34:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-05-08 06:36:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(3 comments)

Anant Patil	

Thank you, replied you in lines.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-05-08 08:29:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 7193, 'date': '2015-05-08 12:41:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Agree to Steven's comments. As I said some time earlier, I am not convinced by the use case, and think this brings in a number of additional assumptions and complexity in signalling, error handling, mapping of input/output parameters etc."}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-05-11 01:18:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

Steven, Thomas,

Thank you. As I replied in lines, add a new 'configs' property can make things better? What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 6348, 'date': '2015-06-15 02:52:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Cleanup wording for the disable_libvirt_livesnapshot workaround option

The config options go in the docs so the help on them should be clear,
especially for workaround options since they are for known issues and
people have to opt-in to using them.

This clears up the wording in the disable_libvirt_livesnapshot option.

Note the change from 'mechanism to disable' to 'mechanism to enable'
since the feature is disabled by default, so the option is actually
providing the mechanism to enable the feature if you want to use it
provided the known issues with libvirt 1.2.2.

Change-Id: Ibb42e0b1ca7c6991ed1b189455b5279f9b12cfff

I don't really like this approach, we should go with partial templates which are cleaner and provide much more flexibility.    This will only really for work for 1 wrapper cookbook, not multiples of them."}, {'account_id': 9488, 'date': '2015-05-04 06:10:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Mark, I don't think partial template is a good solution, because it still need user to define the section with options/values."}, {'account_id': 7128, 'date': '2015-05-04 15:06:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Zhiwei, I understand that a partial means defining a template with sections/keys/values, but with that de-coupling brings a much greater amount of flexibility for future expansion.    I really don't like have an attribute be a bottle-neck for entire template sections, it just means that collisions and updates will be very difficult to manage.   With a partial template approach, we just leave the implementation up to the user and not control what or how they update a template."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-12 17:46:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Allow setting new sections/options in nova.conf

Currently users can only add custom options in DEFAULT section,
with this patch, users are able to add new sections/options in
nova.conf.

Change-Id: I469d3f71ca3c33b405016d20c4b3771f4f329e61

[{'created': '2015-06-02 08:47:10.000000000', 'message': 'Fix 'format' checking for json schema validation

In json schema, "format" keyword is defined to allow inter-operable
semantic validation for a fixed subset of values.
For example - ip address which comes as 'string' can be further checked
with ipv4 or ipv6 format.

ip_address = {
    'type': 'string',
    'oneOf': [
        {'format': 'ipv4'},
        {'format': 'ipv6'}
    ]
}

Json schema does not validate 'format' correctly if FormatChecker is not
passed during validation. Without FormatChecker, it validate all format as true.

To validate 'format' correctly FormatChecker has to be passed while doing schema
validation.

This commit fix this issue.

commit_message:
Fix 'format' checking for json schema validation

In json schema, "format" keyword is defined to allow inter-operable
semantic validation for a fixed subset of values.
For example - ip address which comes as 'string' can be further checked
with ipv4 or ipv6 format.

ip_address = {
    'type': 'string',
    'oneOf': [
        {'format': 'ipv4'},
        {'format': 'ipv6'}
    ]
}

Json schema does not validate 'format' correctly if FormatChecker is not
passed during validation. Without FormatChecker, it validate all format as true.

To validate 'format' correctly FormatChecker has to be passed while doing schema
validation.

This commit fix this issue and adds unit tests for that.

Closes-Bug:1460975

Change-Id: Iad6ec9644eb1ec976b4a47f7dec127bfaecfd1fa

commit_message:
Dispose DB connections between backend proc starts

Currently we do not dispose the existing DB pools before
forking off additional storage backend processes.  This can
result in timing issues and DB errors.

This change simply ensures that we do a dispose_engine() in
the loop where we are forking off processes for the storage
backends.

Change-Id: I4ce67e1ce7853fafe5318393482d841583e42098
Closes-bug: 1463580
(cherry picked from commit bb683d6ce4f8e8ad6f1ba657eac5c7f92c9ea82f)

commit_message:
libvirt: Don't try to confine a non-NUMA instance

Even though it seemed like a good idea at the time, it turns out that
choosing a NUMA node at random can lead to placements that are
suboptimal.

Since the benefit of the current approach is unclear, and the downside
is actually hurting users - it is best to remove it (we would be no
worse off than before Nova was even NUMA aware), and think about
optimizitaions going forward, if any.

Change-Id: Idd4d5c236067fc40ed3a5049f3c1a58b75f9b5e5
Closes-bug: #1461777

commit_message:
Replace urllib and urllib2 with six.moves.urllib

The Python 2 urllib and urllib2 modules changed a lot in Python 3. On
Python 3, the urllib functions are now grouped into submodules of
urllib: urllib.parse, urllib.error, etc. The urllib2 has been removed.
Replace urllib and urllib2 with six.moves.urllib to make the Cinder code
compatible with Python 2 and Python 3.

The new code now looks like Python 3 code (ex: "urllib.parse.urlsplit"),
but it also works on Python 2.

Replace also "import six.moves.urllib.parse as urlparse" with "from
six.moves import urllib" to uniformize the code:
"urlparse.urlsplit(href)" becomes "urllib.parse.urlsplit(href)".

This patch was generated by the urllib operation of the sixer tool version 0.4:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Manual changes:

* Add a try/except ImportError to get the parse_http_list function
  in cinder/api/urlmap.py
* Import the socket module instead of using urllib2.socket
  in cinder/volume/drivers/huawei/rest_common.py
* test_nimble.py: replace NIMBLE_URLLIB2 value with
  'six.moves.urllib.request'
* Remove "from six.moves.urllib import parse as urlparse", it was
  replaced with urllib.parse from six.moves.
* Reformat to respect the 80 columns constraint

Change-Id: Ibd1e7bc83bbbd93a3634207fb277d25ef1b8a086

commit_message:
Add env storing for loaded environments

If env loaded from outer file, there is probability
that this outer file will be deleted. So, if template
uses some resource with resource registry env, we need
to store this env in db.

Change-Id: Ib0c191db2dccac6d467a9961062424bc1f924c24
Closes-bug: #1429141
(cherry picked from commit d8fe35eee518036eab7f73aca28cf4d770ae7dc1)

commit_message:
Fix folder name and update docker-compose version

Fixes folder name for script. Pins fedora base image to f21,
as latest fedora base image(f22) has number of changes that
breaks docker build. Upgrades docker-compose to latest
version that supports `--pid=host` (required by tripleo).

Change-Id: Ia4e32f1461bfc9278e25c9236dc911f1b9c4e876

One question, multi-attach is intended to be a Cinder feature and has an API and all right?  I'm not sure, but are there many (any) drivers that won't be able to support multi-atttach?  In general iSCSI just "supports" this, so I'm wondering if rather than having to run through and change all the drivers to say "multiattach=True" if we should be doing this the other way around.  Make the default get in the filter-scheduler be "True" and those that can't do it have to opt out and set "False".

This mean less duplication, more reuse, and less noise in the capability reporting.

commit_message:
3PAR enable multiattach capability reporting

This patch enables the reporting of the
multiattach capability in get_volume_stats.
The scheduler currently filters on the capability
for drivers that support/don't support that ability
to do more than one attachment for a volume.
By reporting multiattach = True, it lets the scheduler
know this driver allows attaching a volume more than once.

Change-Id: Ia18414bbadff14777c2266b681c03c76a2aa6889

commit_message:
Use six to fix imports on Python 3

Replace Python 2 imports with six.moves import to make code compatible
with Python 2 and Python 3.

Replaced imports:

* BaseHTTPServer
* __builtin__
* cookielib
* httplib

This patch was generated by the six_moves operation of the sixer tool
version 0.4:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Manual changes:

* Disable pylint warnings on the HTTPSConnection classes because pylint
  doesn't support importing from six.moves yet, see:
  https://bitbucket.org/logilab/pylint/issue/550/

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ide6d4e3480f2c0a7eb4500aa88affe152ecc0401

commit_message:
san driver: don't use relative Python import

Replace relative import with absolute import. Relative imports don't
work on Python 3 anymore.

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ie27ee7d8734c59d0739b8e1a2ecc369801d56cf7

commit_message:
Added pylint checks. Fixed import error during python-novaclient import.

Finally pylint checks are executed now during the build.
Currently, as pylint is just enabled, checks for
Warnings, Refactor, Convention are disabled.

Closes bug: 1465063

Change-Id: I1a5447d7a7c2ec717e21aae67d26b0586edad7a5

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-14 02:15:38.000000000', 'message': "Remove db-access semaphore and use db retry instead

The ML2 plugin was using a semaphore to avoid deadlocks
in the C mysql driver because it issues a with_lockmode('update')
on the port and binding tables. This worked when the mysql driver
was guarunteed not to yield while holding the update, but that
is no longer the case with the pymysql driver.

This patch adds a db retry decorator to the method that attempts
to select the tables in update mode.

A follow up patch can be added after pymysql is the default to
completely remove the db-access semaphores as well since they will
no longer serve the purpose they intended.

Change-Id: I6ec70321f38d01120e1964d4521cf23abd814b26
Partial-Bug: #1464612
"}, {'created': '2015-06-14 02:25:24.000000000', 'message': "Add db retry decorator to get_locked_port_and_binding

The ML2 plugin uses a semaphore to avoid deadlocks
in the C mysql driver because it issues a with_lockmode('update')
on the port and binding tables. This worked when the mysql driver
was guarunteed not to yield while holding the update, but that
is no longer the case with the pymysql driver.

This patch adds a db retry decorator to the
get_locked_port_and_binding method that attempts to select the tables
in update mode.

A follow up patch can be added after pymysql is the default to
completely remove the db-access semaphores as well since they will
no longer serve the purpose they intended.

"}]
commit_message:
Add db retry decorator to get_locked_port_and_binding

The ML2 plugin uses a semaphore to avoid deadlocks
in the C mysql driver because it issues a with_lockmode('update')
on the port and binding tables. This worked when the mysql driver
was guarunteed not to yield while holding the update, but that
is no longer the case with the pymysql driver.

This patch adds a db retry decorator to the
get_locked_port_and_binding method that attempts to select the tables
in update mode.

A follow up patch can be added after pymysql is the default to
completely remove the db-access semaphores as well since they will
no longer serve the purpose they intended.

Partial-Bug: #1464612
Change-Id: I6ec70321f38d01120e1964d4521cf23abd814b26

commit_message:
Fixed import error on bin/freezerc

In bin/freezerc was being import the fail function from
freezer/main.py but the function wasn't callable.

Closes bug: 1465062

Change-Id: I0dcba66fd68550449c2a1c90144039e56e4ef915

commit_message:
Replace it.next() with next(it) for py3 compat

The Python 2 next() method of iterators was renamed to __next__() on
Python 3. Use the builtin next() function instead which works on Python
2 and Python 3.

This patch was generated by the next operation of the sixer tool:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Manual changes:

* cinder/tests/unit/test_cmd.py: use "tpgs = iter([tpg])" instead of
  using a magic mock for tpgs

Blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I261f8cda231d80910f27b9c1329f1d43ccdd77b6

commit_message:
Increase default timeout for agents response to 1 hour

Makes this parameter configurable and it can be changed
in config file and/or in app definitions.

commit_message:
cleanup openstack-common.conf and sync updated files

periodic updates of latest from oslo-incubator. please
note that files no longer on oslo-incubator mean that
they have been moved to oslo.* libraries. So there's
more work needed to remove these files and switch
to appropriate libraries

commit_message:
Make the default file encoding a class constant with a docstring

Having this exposed makes it easier to know what it is being
used for and what the default is (and also makes it show up
in generated docs, so people can read all about it).

Change-Id: I2e0f85d9c087d220671e2dbf82d497677c462a9e

commit_message:
Remove testing using persistence sqlalchemy backend with 'mysqldb'

It appears no longer recommended to test against and/or use
mysqldb as a backend that is tested against (since it lacks real
support and development) and it is now better to just test against
pymysql which is under development (and has better eventlet integration
and py3.x support).

Change-Id: I08f7ea67fbeb2e8b2976aef442ed442e33c77e09

commit_message:
Improve the hint message

Currently, we can get scoped token (domain scoped, project scoped)
as well as unscoped token.

When we use OSC to get a domain scoped token without explicitly set
domain information, the hint message show us we need to set a scoped
domain or project, but it miss that the parameters to be set in order
to get project or domain scoped token is not the same.

Thus, the hint message could be improved to make it more clear to
end user.

Change-Id: I94768c619b30be18737fec189ae6d81e81ba090d

It's not necessarily in scope for this change, but I think it would be a good idea to include some way to catch inadvertently long-running write transactions. I would very much like to push db transactions outside the boundaries of just the Nova db api. However, that introduces the possibility that somebody might inadvertently create a write transaction, write to the db (locking some rows), copy 20G of data over a piece of wet string, write some more to the db, then commit. Perhaps a rate-limited log message when a write transaction exceeds time N between creation and commit, where N is a config param.

Don't think long running read transactions would be a problem. Would they?

In related news, should a read transaction be allowed to select for update? Would there be any way to prevent it? I was thinking of this specifically as a way to do atomic reads of multiple key/value tables where a cartesian join isn't feasible. e.g.:

select parent for update
select from k/v where parent
commit

an update would do:

select parent for update
insert/delete from k/v where parent
commit"}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-12-11 14:17:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

re: long running write transactions.   it's easy to catch these here as we just can do time.time() - started and log a warning.  but first off, are long-running write transactions an observed issue?  Also I'd consider long running reads to be a problem as well as that indicates queries taking too long.   usually we find these sort of things using normal "slow query logs" on the MySQL side.   I'd favor looking into 1st class solutions to this kind of thing such as what New Relic does (I'm pretty sure there are profiling/performance metrics things I've seen people working on for openstack specifically).


re: select for update.  We need to stop using select for update across the board in any case as it is not compatible with Galera.  This has been already in progress as you see various functions which rely upon this being rewritten to use optimistic approaches.

But then as far as reader transactions, no, it doesn't make sense to do select for update in a reader transaction as SFU is entirely intended to complement a write.   as far as trying to prevent, again I'm skeptical that we want to be nannying too much here, there are ways to detect that such a statement has been used but it's probably easier just to detect actual writing statements.   the API here can at least disallow session.flush() from proceeding, that would be quite easy.   detecting more subtle things like session.execute(table.insert()), doable but probably overkill.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-12-11 14:25:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

Subclassing __deepcopy__ doesn't work afaict, because the default __deepcopy__ doesn't seem to be recursive. i.e. if the top object (NovaContext in this case) doesn't implement __deepcopy__ it falls through to the pickle thing. Implementing __deepcopy__ was my first thought, too, but I couldn't make it work.

I have made a relatively minor change to NovaContext which works round the issue. It implements to_dict and from_dict. I've strung these together in place of deepcopy, which only copies named attributes, which seems to work."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-01-08 14:53:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19: Code-Review-1

Hmm, no. That's not going to fly for long:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/db/sqlalchemy/api.py#L1214

See how here we're now propagating the elevated context? This means we need to either pass 2 contexts to instance_get_by_uuid, or ensure that the elevated context contains our session.

Modifying NovaContext to explicitly copy the session, if present, would be exceptionally ugly."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-01-08 15:02:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19:

from oslo_db.sqlalchemy.enginefacade import session_from_context as dbsession

def foo_get(context):
    session = dbsession(context)

It's far from syntactically awful, and completely safe wrt context if you implement it with a weak dict."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-01-08 15:06:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

... that would still break when you copied NovaContext and tried to to look up the session for elevated. Tricky.'}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-01-08 15:48:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 19:

Hmm, don't know what I was doing wrong before, but apparently __deepcopy__ *is* called recursively. Defining:

def __deepcopy__(self, memo):
  return self

on both Session and _TransactionContext is enough to make this go away."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-08 18:53:47.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 20.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-08 18:55:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

to support deepcopy() without any surprises, it needs a lot more than that, but having our system be compatible with deepcopy() is probably the easiest way to support this case.  Patchset 20 adds this functionality using linked _TransactionContext objects.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-08 19:21:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 21.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-08 21:23:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21: Verified-1

I had a conversation with John Garbutt earlier today which left me with reservations about how we're using the slave database. I've posted to the ML about it, but I'm expecting to want to make a change here. I think we might want to be able to pass use_slave to anything which specifies a reader. e.g.:

    with enginefacade.using_reader(context, use_slave=True):
        ...

That would essentially mark this as a read-only transaction where out-of-date data is ok. This would be accompanied by a default of use_slave=False.

Let's hold off on making any changes for the moment. Hopefully we'll get some useful feedback."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-30 18:30:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 34:

this is not how it should work.  The default for reader() should be use_slave=True.   The use case of reader() running within a writer() is already handled; if the enclosing transaction is a writer, the reader uses that same transaction.  the use case of a reader() that occurs after a writer() is handled by the fact that writer() committed the transaction.  Using the replication schemes we have such as galera, the transaction is atomically available elsewhere.  

if we put use_slave=False in reader(), then we've solved absolutely nothing.  The whole world will ignore the flag and we'll still be stuck doing all database operations on a single node."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-01-30 19:55:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 34:

with further consideration, as noted on the mailing list thread, has convinced me that no matter what new directives or flags we add, none of them should be "use_slave".  The should remain as declarations of intent only: "I need to write data"; "I need to read data"; "I need to read data that is fully synchronized".  Galera cluster features synchronous replication.  Other cluster setups may not.  Therefore enginefacade would need to choose different strategies in order to suit these intents.  The calling application should only state intent.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-01-30 20:07:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 34: Verified-1
