(6 comments)

I think sync/async needs some more work.

Also, I now think we need a solution for retry on deadlock in the first instance. The reason is this function:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/db/sqlalchemy/api.py#L178

It's there because we currently get db deadlocks. You can search logstash for them: they're definitely around. We need to get rid of these, but in the meantime not handling them would be a regression, and they're going to be hard to find. That retry logic assumes a new transaction on each iteration. As we're taking over transaction management, we need to do that. We can't currently apply @reader or @writer to any function also decorated with _retry_on_deadlock, which is most of the critical ones.

We would also need this for Galera multi-master, but that's not the immediate concern.

How about a new context manager for retry on deadlock, and a new decorator @writer_with_retry which uses it? I would expect most instances of @writer to use @writer_with_retry instead, but I think it's best to be explicit that something might re-execute your code.

Thoughts?"}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-06 16:11:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 37:

retry on deadlock would probably need to call upon "with transaction()" to start a new transaction.  That can be called at which point all @writer / @reader contained within should be using that new transaction.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-06 16:13:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 37:

also, that's the retry on deadlock function, not enginefacade.   let's merge enginefacade, so that the guts of it can begin proving themselves via the LegacyEngineFacade for starters."}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-02-09 12:13:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 37:

Well we could, but LegacyEngineFacade uses none of the interesting code. We wouldn't really be testing anything worth testing.

If we left this as is, I wouldn't see a compelling reason to implement this in Nova beyond using the LegacyEngineFacade. For me, the drivers behind doing this were:

* Atomic updates through transactions spanning multiple db api calls
* Improved database performance due to improved transaction use

If I have blown hot and cold on this patch, it is because the above is what I'm interested in. As my understanding of the problem space has improved, I have found real reasons why this patch isn't going to achieve what I was hoping for. While a minor syntactic cleanup might be slightly interesting, in my view it's not worth the significant amount of donkey work required to do this thoroughly in Nova. If we can't achieve tangible benefits, I'm just not that excited about it.

Let me explain why this patch, as it stands, does not achieve the above. We will consider a single function:

    @_retry_on_deadlock
    def instance_update(context, ...):

Notice that it isn't marked as @writer. That's because the @writer semantics are implemented in _retry_on_deadlock:

    def _retry_on_deadlock_wrapper(context, *args, **kwargs):
        while True:
            try:
                with context.transaction().using_writer():
                    return f(context, *args, **kwargs)
            except db_exc.DBDeadlock:
                ...

Incidentally, my current understanding of MySQL (and moreso for Galera) semantics is that this wrapper is required for every @writer, so @writer will never actually be used.

So, everything calling instance_update (or any @writer function) will always start a new transaction. If the callers wants to make multiple atomic changes, they can't do that. This was one of my drivers, and it can't be achieved. The only way to get round this is to pull this wrapper out of api.py and make it the responsibility of the caller. That's worse, because we're suddenly pushing a ton of boilerplate all across the codebase, and introducing subtle bugs if it's forgotten.

Retry on deadlock has to be associated with the creation of a write transaction. As the new enginefacade is the creator of the write transaction, the only reasonable way to implement this behaviour is to do it in enginefacade. Enginefacade doesn't do this, or expose a way to do this.

But wait... it gets worse. Because MySQL uses repeatable read by default, and all @writers require their own new transactions, if a caller does create its own transaction, then calls out to a writer function, it will not be able to see the results of that 'sub'-transaction without restarting. i.e. An encompassing transaction is unusable anyway.

...and it gets worse. By forcing the writes into a separate transaction, if we're using read slaves on Galera we're encoding the pathological non-synchronous reads behaviour. I.e. we have a single thread which writes in transaction A, then immediately starts read transaction B and expects consistent data. This is a race condition factory, which is ironic because that's what we're trying to move away from.

I appreciate you want to move on with this patch. However, without addressing these fundamental correctness issues, I see plenty of downside and no upside to actually implementing this. By all means put it in oslo.db, but I personally wouldn't be in favour of implementing it in Nova."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-09 17:16:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 37:

Matt -

So I'm about to spend a lot of time responding to all of these concerns, and I am hoping that
my responses get through on this; I've addressed these concerns many times on IRC and
in emails and I see nothing new here, and it's taking a lot of time that I need to
keep repeating them.    As I mentioned on IRC, I can illustrate code that
can solve the problems you refer to, so I ask that you please allow me the
time to produce this code for you, as responding to these comments and emails
has been extremely time consuming and takes away from time spent implementing
the approaches I've already mentioned I will provide.

Let's start off with the most basic thing.

> However, without addressing these fundamental correctness issues, I see plenty of downside and no upside to actually implementing this.

If we took every single concern that you've listed above, and
considered them all to be 100% true, the current situation of Nova
without enginefacade is **far worse** that what you have described.
You refer to many situations where you have the perception that new
transactions will be created that are isolated from each other; this
is generally untrue, as I will describe.   However.  The current
situation of  Nova is that **all** of these cases **do** create brand
new, isolated-from-each-other transactions, right now, in **vastly
more** scenarios than just what you refer to here. To assert that
enginefacade in its current state, even if your misconceptions about
it were true, does not vastly improve upon Nova is very misguided.
Please review some of the current **broken things** in Nova that will
be fixed immediately, even if everything in this list of concerns is
true, in the original blueprint at
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/125181/.  Right now virtually **all**
Nova methods run in distinct transactions and in some cases a
transaction-per-record is produced as well.   These areas will all be
fixed, even if no improvements to the retry decorator are made.

Next, we have to consider two different potential approaches regarding retries;
there has been some discussion concerning to what extent the @retry decorator
should be applied; either in the scope of methods that are known to experience
deadlock, or on virtually all methods.   This issue is related to enginefacade,
but is an external one, and the solution to it will build upon enginefacade,
which is why its essential to at least get enginefacade merged and implemented
in Nova right now as a first step.

Let's first put to rest the notion that we would have an explicit @retry decorator
on virtually all methods.   Because, if we did want retry on all writers, then
obviously this would be implicitly part of what @writer does.
It's been suggested on some on the ML that we do this.  However, I'm not sure
we can make that decision right now, and I have concerns that a retry-on-deadlock
is really appropriate for all writer methods.    The important point here is
that this decision does not have to be made in order to merge enginefacade.

Let's consider then that for at least the time being, we want to leave @retry
only in those places where it lives right now.   It lives in about 12 places
right now in sqlalchemy/api.py.    As stated before, every single one of
these methods already includes:

	@require_context
	@_retry_on_deadlock
	def instance_destroy(context, instance_uuid, constraint=None):
	    session = get_session()
	    with session.begin():

So again I reiterate:  the current situation is already as bad, and worse,
than what you describe.  Retries are already in separate transactions.
If you are concerned that there is some error condition that enginefacade will
introduce, I can allay those concerns, because they are there already.

As discussed in Jay's post [1] regarding concurrency in Nova, the prevalence
of these decorators and the need to retry things on "deadlock" will be
reduced dramatically by moving to the compare-and-swap approach.   I'm hoping
its the case that an actual retry is rare enough that we can in fact push
the retry mechanism up to the top as a largely implicit @writer thing.  That is
fine, but I don't know that we can just implement that across-the-board right now.

> Notice that it isn't marked as @writer. That's because the @writer semantics are implemented in _retry_on_deadlock:

	def _retry_on_deadlock_wrapper(context, *args, **kwargs):
		while True:
		try:
			with context.transaction().using_writer():
				return f(context, *args, **kwargs)
		except db_exc.DBDeadlock:

So, that is basically the current retry_on_deadlock that's ported directly to
enginefacade.   What is missing from this is that if we have a @retry method call
upon another @retry method, it ends up having two levels of transactions and
retries which is the fundamental concern of your post, and the only one that
is actually accurate.   As I've mentioned, I will produce for you a retry_on_deadlock
wrapper that is context-aware for reentrant calls.   This means, that if
one @retry method calls upon another @retry, **they use the same transaction**.
Period.  This will be a solved problem.  You do not need to worry about it.
If I have to change enginefacade, then I will; but please note that the usage
API doesn't change here; the work of merging enginefacade and porting it
to Nova even naively for starters should be continued at the fastest pace possible.
Even if the solution was something like a change of @writer to @writer_w_deadlock,
which I don't think it will be, working on a Nova that is already ported this
is just a simple search and replace.

> Incidentally, my current understanding of MySQL (and moreso for Galera) semantics is that this wrapper is required for every @writer, so @writer will never actually be used.

That needs to be discussed and I don't know that we can make that assertion right now.
But as I said before, if we need retry-on-deadlock for every @writer, then of course
we will make it implicit.   This change can be made to enginefacade, **anytime**.
It does not preclude being able to merge enginefacade and produce the Nova
implementation, which, note again, **already does things in the worst way possible**.

> But wait... it gets worse. Because MySQL uses repeatable read by default, and all @writers require their own new transactions,

This is incorrect.  @writers don't require their own new transactions.   The @retry
system will be architected such that all retries share the same outermost retry.

> ...and it gets worse. By forcing the writes into a separate transaction, if we're using read slaves on Galera we're encoding the pathological non-synchronous reads behaviour.

Also incorrect.  Calling @reader inside of @writer, or critically (as I think you misunderstand this)
calling @reader underneath the auspices of "with context.transaction()", **uses that new transaction**.
Please refer to tests such as test_external_connection_transaction and
test_external_session_transaction in test_enginefacade.py.  These tests assert
that when code is called within the "with context.transaction()" block, that new transaction
now takes effect for **all** @writer and @reader calls contained within.   So the
non-synchronous read issue (if that even is an issue) is not apparent in this case.

Please allow me the time to produce a @_retry_on_deadlock decorator which
integrates with enginefacade.   I will produce it as part of the @wrap_db_retry
system already present in oslo.db (which note, Nova does not use, and if you
can get them to use it, that would be great).  As it is part of oslo.db I probably
will integrate it deeply with enginefacade's internals, though as long as @_retry_on_deadlock
is not implicit for all @writers, I still think it should be a separate decorator
as a Python decorator is most appealing when it is declarative of exactly one
intent.   This will also ensure that it remains usable for projects like Keystone
who explicitly do not want to use @writer, they want to use the context manager
version.   The new retry on deadlock will integrate with these just as nicely.

To recap:

* Nova's current state is much worse than what's stated here, an enginefacade
  that solves none of the above issues is still vastly better than the current status.
  Implementing enginefacade within it even naively is a vast improvement.

* @_retry_on_deadlock will proceed either as global to all @writers, or as it
  remains implemented on particular hot spot methods, but in no case will it
  cause multiple transactions to be created within nested calls.  There will
  be a single, top level transaction and retry for the whole operation;
  @_retry_on_deadlock calls within will automatically join into the larger
  retry / transaction.  Individual
  @writer and @reader calls within the retry will also share the same transaction,
  as this is how enginefacade already works.

* oslo.db has a @retry decorator that is great and I will implement the improvements
  here.   However, I don't know why its been so difficult to get other projects
  to use it, which is why I didn't try to make it a "day one" part of enginefacade.

* The new @_retry_on_deadlock, as long as it remains an explicit directive, needs
  to remain a decorator that is syntactically independent of @writer, since
  not every project will use @writer as a decorator.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-09 17:18:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 37:

[1] Jay's post: http://www.joinfu.com/2015/01/understanding-reservations-concurrency-locking-in-nova/"}, {'account_id': 9555, 'date': '2015-02-10 11:46:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 37:

> So I'm about to spend a lot of time responding to all of these concerns,
> and I am hoping that my responses get through on this;

I'm sensing a little frustration here, Mike ;) That's ok, but please understand that I feel the same way. Hopefully we're just talking at cross purposes. However, until we get to the bottom of that, I still don't feel I have effectively communicated my concerns.

Also, please bear in mind that if my concerns are valid, and having read your response I remain confident they are, any time spent now will pay dividends later.

> However. The current situation of Nova is that **all** of these cases
> **do** create brand new, isolated-from-each-other transactions, right now,
> in **vastly more** scenarios than just what you refer to here. To assert
> that enginefacade in its current state, even if your misconceptions about
> it were true, does not vastly improve upon Nova is very misguided.

This might be at the heart of the issue. Don't focus on a single point here; the problems are caused by an interaction of multiple issues. Enginefacade introduces 2 new behaviours:

* Expanded transaction scope
* Increased use of read slaves

I am in favour of both of these. However, these new, desirable features also introduce new semantics. If current code cannot deal with those semantics, we can't implement them without making matters worse. So I fully understand your point that the net result will be fewer transactions. However, the interaction of those transactions will be worse, and the result will be worse.

Expanded transaction scope introduces problems to current code when you end up nesting transactions (bear with me, I'll explain why we will end up nesting transactions below). Imagine a block of code which currently does this:

    foo_create():
        Transaction A {
            insert into foo...
        }
    thing_which_reads_foo():
        Transaction B {
            select from foo...
        }

2 things to note in the current code:

1. There is no nesting.

2. It doesn't use a read slave for transaction B.

With enginefacade, it becomes this (bear with me on the nested transaction):

    Writer transaction A {
        foo_create():
            Writer transaction B {
                insert into foo..
            }

        thing_which_reads_foo():
            select from foo...
    }

This doesn't work, because transaction A uses repeatable read. The fact that it has avoided creating an additional transaction for thing_which_reads_foo() means that this function no longer works. i.e. The new enginefacade semantics have broken it.

Ok, the caller knows that foo_create() will create a new transaction (bear with me on this) and therefore can't be nested. They instead do this:

    foo_create():
        Writer transaction A {
            insert into foo...
        }

    thing_which_reads_foo():
        Reader transaction B {
            select from foo...
        }

So, they've explicitly removed the enclosing transaction, which forces each of the called functions to create their own transactions. Except that with the new enginefacade we're now making maximum use of read slaves. Transaction A writes data to the write master, and transaction B expects to read it from a read slave a fraction of a millisecond later. This is going to race, and the likelihood of failure is extremely high. Note that we have never used read slaves like this in Nova before.

Incidentally, note that this is what you get if all you did was annotate foo_create as @writer and thing_which_reads_foo() as @reader. i.e. Even if the only thing you did was add annotations, you still broke it on Galera.

So, there are 2 circumstances in which the above code will work correctly:

1. It all executes in a single transaction.

2. It uses separate transactions on the same database node.

Circumstance 2 is what we have currently, but when we add @reader annotations we break it, as they will be pushed to a read slave. So, the only way this can be correct is if we have a single transaction.

i.e. We can only safely create enclosing transactions if we *never* create nested transactions.

I already highlighted the problem in the current version of _retry_on_deadlock requiring transaction nesting. You've said you'll solve that and I'm very confident you will. However, bear in mind that we can *never* nest write transactions if we're using repeatable read. Transactions may be disjoint, but they must execute on the same database node.

However, even assuming _retry_on_deadlock is a solved problem wrt nested write transactions, there are still places in the current code which *require* separate write transactions for correctness when using repeatable read. I highlighted 3 of them in my recent ML post here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-February/056245.html

Remember, separate write transactions are broken with the new enginefacade because they are either nested, and therefore always broken (when using repeatable read), or potentially disjoint with a reader on a separate node, and therefore racy with a very high probability of failure. Neither of these things are true if we are not using enginefacade.

I'm not going to go over the specifics in the above ML post again here, but let me refer to Jay's blog post linked in a comment above. That blog post makes the argument for compare-and-swap, which is something I'm also in favour of, and points out that we want to do more of this in Nova. Compare-and-swap implies a retry loop. A retry loop requires a separate transaction if you're using repeatable read. A separate transaction is broken when created in the context of an existing transaction if you're using repeatable read. i.e. We can *never* gain the benefit of enginefacade's expanded transaction scope.

How to move forward? Well, in order to just add annotations to existing Nova code we need to solve the disjoint write/read transaction problem on separate Galera nodes. That is, we can't do anything at all until we're doing wsrep_causal_reads. Note that this is *not* an issue of multiple RPCs, and it has never been an issue in Nova before because we have never used read slaves this way. This is an issue of the same RPC which has no enclosing transaction calling a @writer and then a @reader within a millisecond of each other, and expecting consistent data.

I see 2 ways forward for expanded transaction scope, but you may have more:

1. Move from repeatable read to read committed.

This will allow us to have increased transaction scope without requiring separate transactions for the various retry scenarios. I think this would be very easy.

2. Re-evaluate the goal of increased transaction scope.

This would be a naval-gazing moment for the concept of attaching a database transaction to a RequestContext object and attempting to re-use it. However, I'm starting to wonder."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-02-10 17:38:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 37:

> However, bear in mind that we can *never* nest write transactions if we're using repeatable read.

you can't make that assertion in the abstract, because this is specific to the data being worked upon:

1. if the nested transaction deals with a row that the enclosing transaction never needs to SELECT
or UPDATE, there is no issue.

2. if the nested transaction deals with a row that the enclosing transaction has *not yet* SELECT/UPDATEed,
there is no issue; the enclosing transaction will read the row in its updated state
if its first read is after the nested transaction has worked.  Demonstration: http://paste.openstack.org/show/170853/

3. for INSERTs, RR is irrelevant.   RR does not prevent phantom reads

The RR-nesting issue described is only possible if all of the following criteria are met:

1. the enclosing transaction emits a SELECT/UPDATE for the row in question, *before*
the nested transaction is called.  This establishes the current version
of the row as significant within the transaction.
2. the nested transaction emits an UPDATE for the row in question.  This creates
a new version of the row.
3. the enclosing transaction then emits a *second* SELECT/UPDATE for the row in question,
*after* the nested transaction is called.  Or it somehow relies upon the old
version of that row in its subsequent logic. 

This scenario seems unusual to me, that a method would deal with some row, then 
call upon another routine which would modify that row, then the enclosing routine reads it again.  I'm sure Nova can pull this off, but I'd imagine the easy solution is just to ensure the retry is placed at an appropriately high level (which, if we can move towards all methods being retryable, would be the easy solution).

This is why its critical that you illustrate your scenario in real, reproducing tests.
Nested transactions that both need to operate upon the same row in an UPDATE
context seems very unusual, and I would think that the solution to this would be
to just move the retry activity up one level."}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-03-02 21:49:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 38.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2015-03-02 21:53:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 38:

this latest version makes a major change to the overall interface of enginefacade.  As we would like to add full support for both "independent" transactions at the decorator/context manager level, as well as for savepoints, the concept of multiplying out all the methods to accomodate these new options was replaced with a new "builder" approach which vastly simplifies the implementation; enginefacade.py has gone from 1132 lines of code to 789.   _TransactionContextManager becomes a stateful builder object, which then invokes its set of options upon the _TransactionContext directly.   The concepts of "writer", "reader", "async", "connection", and now "independent" and "savepoint" as public-facing keywords all exist solely as a single accessor on this object.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-02 23:51:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 38: Verified-1

Change-Id: I9a3d0c26bb727eb2c0bd823b9a12fde57cc7c9c3
'}, {'created': '2014-12-03 22:56:16.000000000', 'message': 'Implement new oslo.db.sqlalchemy.enginefacade module

This module presents a replacement for the EngineFacade
system.  At the center is the oslo.db.sqlalchemy.enginefacade
module, which when imported, provides decorators and context
managers which perform all database and ORM connectivity
functions transparently.   The docstrings as well
as the blueprint provide an introduction.

The patch includes a refactoring of sqlalchemy/session.py
into three dependent modules engines.py, orm.py and
enginefacade.py.  This is to maintain a non-cyclical import
structure as well as to maintain the import behavior of
oslo.db overall, as some projects such as glance currently
have dependencies on this structure.

There is also a slimming down and attempt at modernizing
some very old documentation in session.py.  The enginefacade
system should be preferred moving forward.

bp/make-enginefacade-a-facade

Change-Id: I9a3d0c26bb727eb2c0bd823b9a12fde57cc7c9c3

commit_message:
Implement new oslo.db.sqlalchemy.enginefacade module

This module presents a replacement for the EngineFacade
system.  At the center is the oslo.db.sqlalchemy.enginefacade
module, which when imported, provides decorators and context
managers which perform all database and ORM connectivity
functions transparently.   The docstrings as well
as the blueprint provide an introduction.

The patch includes a refactoring of sqlalchemy/session.py
into three dependent modules engines.py, orm.py and
enginefacade.py.  This is to maintain a non-cyclical import
structure as well as to maintain the import behavior of
oslo.db overall, as some projects such as glance currently
have dependencies on this structure.

There is also a slimming down and attempt at modernizing
some very old documentation in session.py.  The enginefacade
system should be preferred moving forward.

Implements: blueprint make-enginefacade-a-facade

Change-Id: I9a3d0c26bb727eb2c0bd823b9a12fde57cc7c9c3

commit_message:
Return proper response object in Kubernetes APIs

Below list of Kubernetes APIs doesn't return proper response object:

1. createPod
2. replacePod
3. deletePod
4. createReplicationController
5. replaceReplicationController
6. deleteReplicationController
7. createService
8. replaceService
9. deleteService

This patch fix this problem and also change the
impact on magnum code.

Change-Id: Ib8fd9c4ea8766e7a1e7d1a56cc8325ecd518557d
Closes-bug: #1463252

commit_message:
Use oslo.log instead of oslo-incubator logging

log module has been removed from oslo-incubator after oslo.log was
released. This change will fail tests till a new guest image is built
with oslo.log in the requirements.txt file. The change
https://review.openstack.org/162676 has been submitted to get a new
guest image.

Change-Id: I753573c14facf5bf916d6deee8c1cd7f112a9f48
Implements: blueprint port-oslo-incubator-to-oslo-log
Depends-On: I1cb764c6bd978be71c5a9a6dd26d53ebea5192bb

Change-Id: I397a7f76ee2c41a02092882c110ee89b76dce846

changed from edeploy to extra_hardware.

[{'created': '2015-06-08 20:16:42.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Fix edeploy plugin puts too much data in Ironic extra column

The edeploy plugin stores all of the facts it collects in the extra column of
the Ironic db. When using real hardware, edeploy collects a large amount of
facts and can lead to overflowing that column.

This patch fixes this by storing the collected data in Swift instead. This
makes it usable more generically as well. Anything stored on the 'data' key in
the dictionary returned by the ramdisk is stored as a JSON encoded string in
a Swift object. The object is named 'extra_hardware-<node uuid>' and is stored
in the 'inspector' container.

Since this plugin is now usable in a more generic way, the name is changed from
edeploy to extra_hardware.

Change-Id: Ie9e017df735a95350991ce419fa3b64249819d70
Closes-Bug: 1461252

commit_message:
Fix edeploy plugin puts too much data in Ironic extra column

The edeploy plugin stores all of the facts it collects in the extra
column of the Ironic db. When using real hardware, edeploy collects a
large amount of facts and can lead to overflowing that column.

This patch fixes this by storing the collected data in Swift instead.
This makes it usable more generically as well. Anything stored on the
'data' key in the dictionary returned by the ramdisk is stored as a
JSON encoded string in a Swift object. The object is named
'extra_hardware-<node uuid>' and is stored in the 'ironic-inspector'
container.

Change-Id: Ie9e017df735a95350991ce419fa3b64249819d70
Closes-Bug: 1461252

commit_message:
Change updated ports from set to list

The updated ports in the agent base is a list of neutron ports that have
been updated since the last rpc_loop.

It was a set of ports.  However, the port is non-hashable and therefore
can not be added to a set.  This change set moves the container to a
list.

Change-Id: Ic4b65e575efa54d51f0cefa2472f94bfca449675

commit_message:
Set Neutron api_workers to $API_WORKERS

Change [1] brings back this feature in Neutron, so we want to have
the ability to set the number of API workers the same way other
projects do.

However, this cause some instability, so we need to be careful on
how we bring it back.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191127/

Closes-Bug: #1432189
Related-bug: #1432065

Change-Id: Id4986a49d33fa4b8a7291150488665e200525dac
Co-authored-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fix invalid call to parse of empty bridge mapping

The call to parse the empty bridge mappings was not properly formed.  It
resulted in a failed call that will kill the agent.

This change set fixes the bug and adds a unit test so that the path is
now verified.

Change-Id: I567d8592d8cd0d1317d149f6e3b131f145a20cc2

[{'created': '2015-06-01 20:07:39.000000000', 'message': 'Add secondary account capability to SolidFire

The SolidFire Cluster has a limit of 2K volumes per SolidFire
account. Given that the SolidFire account maps directly to the
OpenStack tenant this can be a limitation for some large scale
deployers who may have tenants that wish to create more than
2K volumes in their OpenStack cloud.

This patch introduces the concept of a secondary account for
an OpenStack tenant on the SolidFire backend.

If an OpenStack tenant has more than 2K volumes, and wishes to
create additional volumes, we can create a secodary/supplemental
SolidFire account that is owned by the same OpenStack tenant.

If they wish to go beyond 4K volumes... well, SolidFire V3
driver will deal with that, for now 4K is a line in the sand.

**** WIP ****
Needs tests and the main exception handler implemented.

Change-Id: I1c8a14e6bea1b6f47d10777c56c5af42b63e2dae

commit_message:
Add secondary account capability to SolidFire

The SolidFire Cluster has a limit of 2K volumes per SolidFire
account. Given that the SolidFire account maps directly to the
OpenStack tenant this can be a limitation for some large scale
deployments that may have tenants that wish to create more than
2K volumes in their OpenStack cloud.

This patch introduces the concept of a secondary account for
an OpenStack tenant on the SolidFire backend.

If an OpenStack tenant has more than 2K volumes, and wishes to
create additional volumes, we can create a secondary/supplemental
SolidFire account that is owned by the same OpenStack tenant.

If they wish to go beyond 4K volumes... well, SolidFire V3
driver will deal with that, for now 4K is a line in the sand.

While working on unit tests, we again move to using mock
opportunistically.  In addition, a few tests that either
weren't actually testing anything, or were just a fake-loop
that didn't actually work have been removed:

NOTE:
This patch is a temporary for backporting purposes, we are
still planning a refresh in Liberty of the driver.

Change-Id: I1c8a14e6bea1b6f47d10777c56c5af42b63e2dae

commit_message:
Coalesce port values in secgroup rules

Nova uses -1 for non-specific port values in security group rules.
Neutron rules represent these as None. We need to be consistent in
the values we return from shade, so we'll pick the Neutron way since
we make Nova rules look like Neutron rules anyway.

Change-Id: I6b58c0f9d2f9f11860eade0b6ee2d164e67914b8

(2 comments)

wow, good catch Stan, my bad. I read some ancient documentation that indicated these values were ASN1_UTCTIME, this changed in OpenSSL 0.9.5a to ASN1_TIME as you point out. I have added some work around suggestions for the missing ASN1_TIME_set method that should fix things in the mean time. See comments in source.'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:18:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

It's worth noting that all the various ASN1_* time related structures are just ASN1_STRINGs (cffi enforces the type checking, not OpenSSL) holding the time string in differing formats (YYMMDDHHSS... etc) and a type id  (V_ASN1_GENERALIZEDTIME etc) so it should be perfectly safe to use utctime or generalised time based on the rules given here https://www.openssl.org/docs/crypto/ASN1_TIME_set.html (So I think we can just use generalised time as suggested previously, the code in pyOpenSSL supports this as well)"}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-05-29 15:22:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

confirmed, ASN1_TIME will accept both formats (UTC or generalised) as strings, so the suggested fix should work fine.'}, {'account_id': 1528, 'date': '2015-06-03 06:23:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1528, 'date': '2015-06-03 06:26:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Also, previous patch was incorrect, because the tests themselves checked get result by transforming UTC timestamp into local. This is now corrected in both code and tests."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-03 06:39:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Fix notBefore/notAfter handling in non-UTC time

Use the actual type returned from openssl - ASN1_TIME.
Also, the test itself was incorrect. set_not_...() tests are fixed to
test UTC-based values now and not convert to local timezone.

Cryptography >= 0.9.1 needs to be used due to incompatible interface
changes.

Change-Id: I520e42e5a985f47e9fe8505f9023b8b1d05665b5

commit_message:
Move update.py into the python package.

A symlink is kept to update.py to keep this working for infra until we
update the propose scripts to try the new location and fall back.

Until that is done and the symlink removed, update.py cannot refer to
other modules (though they can refer to it).

Change-Id: If878bc2bb426c0e5478ed031f1144e26f05e85a2

> Victor, thanks for fixing it. Could you please share more details what issues with hacking do you have?

The current Hacking rules are written for Python 2. My sixer tool is very really dummy, it's based on dummy regular expressions. It replaces the "unicode" pattern anywhere, including docstrings and strings. Hacking only uses "unicode" in strings, so I just reverted these useless changes. Anyway, we should *not* replace "unicode" with "six.text_type" since the hacking rules expect exactly the string "unicode" :-)

commit_message:
Replace unicode with six.text_type

The "unicode" type was renamed to "str" in Python 3. Use six.text_type
to make Cinder compatible with Python 3.

The initial patch was generated by the unicode operation of sixer tool:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Manual changes:

* cinder/volume/drivers/san/hp/hp_3par_iscsi.py:
  replace "isinstance(value, str) or isinstance(value, unicode)"
  with "isinstance(value, six.string_types)"
* cinder/volume/drivers/san/hp/hp_3par_iscsi.py:
  bump the version to 2.0.17
* Revert changes on hacking: hacking explicitly searchs the "unicode"
  pattern for Python 2. Hacking may require more work to be ported to
  Python 3.
* Revert changes on docstrings and strings

Change-Id: I68ea8a81a66c9377b2fe20e3f545dce8b691c398

commit_message:
Add version bump guideline in microversion devref

This patch adds some description on how the API can be evolved using API
microversioning, including descriptions of which changes are possible with
and without a microversion bump.

Change-Id: I1d1752eca27f3ab0888b7db8871449dbb3a1eb72

commit_message:
Add describe about extra query parameter

There isn't any guidance about how to process the extra query parameter
in the request. This patch adds it.

Change-Id: Iebb72d9e216f0efa753f2a8e99f39a385d504c26

commit_message:
Pass full path to pkgutil.iter_modules()

On my production system, when using client version 3, an exception is
raised with an incomplete message as the installed novaclient is
failing to find the bundled client versions.  This commit creates a new
_get_available_client_versions() method and moves the client version
searching from get_client_class() into it.

We also update __get_available_client_versions() to pass
pkgutil.iter_modules the full path to novaclient rather than
'novaclient', which is what actually resolves the issue here.

Lastly, we add a single test to ensure that
__get_available_client_versions() does not return an empty list.

Change-Id: I07ce414863e833c72e50ad8cf1824054cfb41457
Closes-Bug: #1463809

Just use d.values() and skip the six messiness please.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-06-10 20:04:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> Just use d.values() and skip the six messiness please.

dict.itervalues() is used for good reasons on Python 2: for efficiency, to avoid the creation of temporary lists.

six.iteritems() and six.itervalues() are now commonly used in OpenStack to support Python 2 and Python 3. See for example changes merged in Nova:

* six.iteritems: I81465661cb8a74778d70ba9b6641073f1effa49b
* six.itervalues: Ied9a76447fbdc933369f926cb19aab9d8896ab92'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2015-06-10 20:15:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

John:
> Just use d.values() and skip the six messiness please.

Ok, you will be happy: I abandon this change and I wrote a new one replacing dict.itervalues() with dict.values(): https://review.openstack.org/#/c/191066/

I prefer itervalues(), but it was decided differently on the openstack-dev mailing list ;-)'}]

commit_message:
Replace dict.itervalues() with six.itervalues(dict)

The itervalues() method of Python 2 dictionaries was renamed to items()
on Python 3. Use six.itervalues() to make the Cinder code compatible
with Python 3.

This patch was generated by the itervalues operation of the sixer tool:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Manual changes:

* Modify cinder/volume/drivers/ibm/storwize_svc/__init__.py to respect
  the constraint of 80 columns

Change-Id: Ib7ba46ff6c3e6006bf15b39e3bdaddd1b1e97053

commit_message:
Stop using tearDown

tearDown doesn't get called when there's an exception in setUp,
which can cause issues with test stability and isolation, so
better to avoid it.

Change-Id: I5ca2d84bcf82f4c88af26b4c582b0f23264a959c

commit_message:
Use mock rather than mox

Switch to mock rather than mox. We should pick one or the other
mocking library, and mock is preferred.

Change-Id: I86ad9638da2f53189fbaea3fd9476356eb0c7ff5

commit_message:
Switch to warnings module instead of versionutils

versionutils.py is no longer in oslo-incubator. So we can
either use versionutils from oslo_log or debtcollector instead.
However, oslo.messaging does not use oslo.log currently and we
should not be adding yet another library as a dependency here,
so we should just use the base python warnings library for
our limited use of deprecated() method.

Change-Id: Ib8a487051c894fa4828da65d4890b7a4f57f1d12

commit_message:
NetApp E-Series driver: Remove caching logic

This patch removes unnecessary API caching logic from the NetApp
E-Series driver. The cache, represented as the _objects dictionary,
is refreshed nearly every API call and therefore provides no value.
This refactor is also preparation for refactoring the class structure
so we can easily add an E-Series Fibre Channel driver.

Change-Id: I5a1a8c9bab3abff58a876a1da3575b1c329fdfba

commit_message:
Volume manager should set filter_function and goodness_function

If a user defines a filter_function or goodness_function in their cinder.conf
file the scheduler should use that function. This change appends those
functions to volume_stats if the driver has not specified them.

Change-Id: I76f90aa3c1bda7564185d8e130926af7d0827e0e
Closes-Bug: #1458061

commit_message:
NetApp E-Series: Add Fibre Channel Support

The NetApp driver for E-series product lines currently support iSCSI. This
patch adds Fibre Channel support to the E-Series driver. This driver reuses
the same functionality as the E-Series iSCSI driver except for the
initialize_connection and terminate_connection driver methods which make
full use of Cinder's FibreChannel zone manager.

DocImpact
Implements blueprint: add-fibre-channel-support-to-netapp-eseries
Co-Authored-By: Alex Meade <mr.alex.meade@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Yogesh Kshirsagar <ykshirsa@netapp.com>

Change-Id: I130f473aaa27ace4cd16a98f75c797aa967715b3

commit_message:
NetApp E-Series: Refactor class structure for FC

This patch moves classes to mimic the NetApp ONTAP drivers class
structure by creating a library module, making the iSCSI driver
a thin layer. This way the E-Series FC driver can be added in a
similar manner.

Change-Id: I8b4ed6a7b2d43cd93da5c340646405e3041a312a

Armando, I'm planning on working on full stack tests to have L2 connectivity tests, under the following scenarios:

OVS agent +
VLANs
VXLAN
VXLAN + l2pop

Finally, add LB agent support with the same scenarios.

I'm considering adding a single fake VM to fake VM connectivity test (Same network, no routing) with all of the above scenarios. We could then add a router and e/w routing, with different router types, but that's for later.

With that said, the test coverage issue here is can and should be plugged with a functional test that would cover the OVS agent (Hey if someone wants to write one for the LB agent go ahead) and call an l2pop fdb_add RPC method on the agent. It will be difficult to parse output of OVS commands to find out if the tunnel device was added and the proper flows were added. Might be easier with the native interface. 

I don't think this functional test addition is required for this patch to merge, but we do need coverage for fdb_add/del with unit tests in this patch."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-06-09 00:09:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Fix a regression in "Separate ovs-ofctl using code as a driver" change

The tunnels are not getting established between Network Node and
Compute Nodes in non DVR mode with l2pop enabled and throws
the AttributeError: add_tunnel_port.

This fixes a regression in change Ie1224f8a1c17268cd7d1c474ed82fdfb8852eaa8.

Co-Authored-By: YAMAMOTO Takashi <yamamoto@midokura.com>
Closes-Bug: #1461486
Change-Id: I1106fd3dd32f6f827eb25dec4815ff1120af96f0

Before mysql migrations disabled foreign key checks only for
mysql+mysqldb engine. Currently mysql+pymysql is preferred engine. This

'}]
commit_message:
Migrations: ignore mysql fk cheks for any mysql driver

Before mysql migrations disabled foreign key checks only for
mysql+mysqldb engine. Currently mysql+pymysql is preferred engine. This
change disables FK checks for any mysql engine available.

Change-Id: I536480559260c4be11b6e615c0df8f012798be9d
Closes-Bug: #1464271

commit_message:
Fix publisher test_udp on Python 3

* Call msgpack.loads() with an encoding to get unicode strings, not
  byte strings
* Sort counters using their name because a counter is a dictionary
  and dictionaries are not comparable in Python 3.
* Add test_udp to tox.ini for Python 3.4.

Change-Id: Ifa20eecbc1c293da667f58843b7a6c2d7f32152c

commit_message:
Fix Ceph object store tests on Python 3

* Fix keystoneclient mock on Python 3: service_catalog.url_for() must
  return a string because urllib.parse.urljoin() is now more strict on
  Python 3
* tox -e py34: add objectstore.test_rgw

Change-Id: I0a4a33a26b7984854c8561866a6f49e2b4d7ff6d

commit_message:
Make measures processing asynchronously

This patches split the measures processing for the Carbonara in
two-phases: first the measures are written as fast as possible, and then
a function is responsible to process them in batch.

Currently this is still done synchronously for the API, but a next patch
will split that into a secondary daemon.

This is not implemented for Ceph.

Change-Id: I08a877bbcf7abb034188c5710ba79f5f81a5a9a0

commit_message:
[networking] howto disable libvirt networking

By default, libvirt configures ts own networking that is unrelated to OpenStack.
This can be confusing for operators trying to troubleshoot OpenStack networking
issues who aren't familiar with how libvirt works or how it relates to
OpenStack.

This patch explains how libvirt networking works and describes how to disable it to
simplify debugging networking issues with OpenStack.

Change-Id: If1570b6acbfe630762e454a3519fff7eeaedddef

commit_message:
TOSCA: create csar for monitoring use case

This CSAR is created for TOSCA monitoring use case and provides a good example
with custom type definitions, shell scripts and python artifacts. It can be
used as is and will be used to to provide support for CSAR translation.

Change-Id: I431d375d921a97b3ca8b62a65286ba1c6d9b0272

commit_message:
Added javascript job template, included in refstack.

This creates a jobs template for various common npm-based
jobs, and a javascript job template that runs two NPM-based
jobs in the gate.

Change-Id: I26fc5b1f780453202af8d1d43575bbf2aa53d27e
Depends-On: Ibd16775609fbfe8f60a14672a27fb44e84fb63b9

commit_message:
Add more parameters to update_port()

While writing an Ansible modules for Neutron port (os_port) it turned
out almost all the parameters passed to create_port() function can be
passed to update_port() as well.
Official Neutron API documentation only mentions 'name',
'admin_state_up', 'fixed_ips' and 'security_groups'.

This patch add all the parameters that can actually be passed to the
Neutron update_port method.

Change-Id: I0e274d882295c7435cbeda529c4f48e2cccd9a79

commit_message:
Add a thread in ConfigFixture to do metricd

Without this the new async processing of measures will cause tests
that check to see if measures were created will fail.

The thread runs the process_measures method in a tight loop.

Meanwhile gabbi >=0.100.0 provides a 'poll' function so that tests
will try a few times for what they are looking for.

The tests in resource.yaml have been cleaned up to insure that they
are testing a specific resource and its measures not an ambiguous
last-in-the-list member of resources.

Change-Id: Id18f4a607ad910fdf6738b225811073c89a03508

commit_message:
Add PUT Support For the Generic Containers Resource

The original intent of the 'generic' container type was to support
arbitrary secrets to be collected and referenced, similar to a file
system folder. Hence it makes sense for an already-created 'generic'
container to support changing this collection after the fact. This
blueprint details how this API would look.

Implements: api-containers-add-put
APIImpact: Add PUT action to the containers resource
DocImpact: Add docs for the new PUT action for containers resource
Change-Id: Ia2c9758436937096ff7d4c5f4ea89c302cc6983a

commit_message:
Migrate some Puppet OpenStack repos under OpenStack namespace

When https://review.openstack.org/#/c/176326/ will be merged, some
Puppet OpenStack modules (called compliant) will be moved under
OpenStack namespace.

This patch aims to update the patch to clone the modules from the new
remote url.

Change-Id: I5a5198e45204d64fbaa27477bdde2914d04b4595
Depends-on: I16d5e03658e72c6f3d1e37b560cfbf85940a8f08

commit_message:
OVSNeutronAgent pass the config as parameter

Instead of using the global cfg.CONF, pass the config as parameter.
This is very useful to test the agent without having to override
the global config.

Change-Id: I45534d79e044da9f2be4d596a58310fb28b7bf22

commit_message:
Create new stackforge project tap-as-a-service

Tap-as-a-Service is a project to introduce the functionality of
port mirroring in OpenStack Neutron provisioned networks.

Change-Id: If8cc9ee64f615d1e9a7e3da6926c9bdb4a93e389
Signed-off-by: vnyyad <vinay.yadhav@ericsson.com>

commit_message:
carbonara: add an option to ignore too old points

The current behavior when sending too old samples is to raise a
NoDeloreanAvailable exception and not doing anything. This patch adds an
option to not raise an exception and treat the valid points anyway,
dropping the too old ones.

Change-Id: Ia5730552eba4118f354711cb123e4b54dbf63dd6

Re-integrate Oracle iSCSI Cinder driver

This reverts commit c742566.

The Oracle iSCSI Cinder driver now has a working CI and is ready to be re-integrated.

Change-Id: I0522dc054a46d62f912df1694d54c0083c5f4f7e

commit_message:
rest: return 202 when posting measures

We used to return 204 No Content to indicate that the metric were stored
and ready to get retrieved. Let's change that to 202 Accepted, which
indicates that the processing is still running, as certain drivers might
not be totally synchronous, e.g. InfluxDB.

Depends-On: I23d313220607fcc8acb95ab43f55b7d9899b9b1f
Change-Id: I5bf35cf6c9b160efba129c1d8919b585403be891

commit_message:
Fixes sync between Arista ML2 driver and EOS

A bug in the sync code prevented the Arista ML2 driver from syncing with EOS.
This patch fixes the bug and adds some unit tests to ensure that the sync
behaves as expected.

This patch is not being submitted as a back-port because the fix
was submitted in stackforge/networking-arista as a part of 
decomposition effort under patch - 
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155940/


Change-Id: I8557496ac8447752d14ba756af2236ad83d1a630
Closes-Bug: 1411383

commit_message:
Update progress lease every 60 seconds

Currently the NFC lease is updated after every written/read chunk. This
is very inefficient because we make many API calls when transfering
large images. The progress can be updated every minute or so which
significantly decreases the overall transfer time.

For example, when importing 900MB streamOptimized image, the overall
time is decreased by 50% with this patch. The improvement for larger
images or slower connections will be even better.

Change-Id: Iba7754e88a43cebb4378a08d2523cfe9645f18e7

commit_message:
Remove useless volume when boot from volume failed

Currently, when boot instance from block device, user can choose three
kinds of sources: (blank, snapshot or image), and compute manager will
create a volume from one of them. But the volume creation may fail or
timeout at this time, then the process of instance boot will fail.

During cleanup, the failed volume cannot be deleted, and becomes unusable.

This patch removes the corresponding volume when block device allocation
fails or times out.

Closes-Bug: #1447884

Change-Id: Ib3c915b5b5920c8289d5fc69cde4a3c485ed8600
(cherry picked from commit 8772653ddec24ae68a0bcd9440e9e6ec81ea301b)

commit_message:
Revert "Switch from MySQL-python to PyMySQL"

Seems like it's not ideal solution under load.
Let's test it in gate under load.

This reverts commit f08e9f1f53efa97e07f21ca72a940fcbeb4570e5.

Closes-bug: #1464363

Changing the default for any set of tests from run to don't run is not good, especially in branchless tempest. These are tested in the gate so you would have to also change the config in devstack on all branches to go along with this. What is not straightforward about changing this value when using tempest?

At some point these tests may be removed from tempest in favor of the new ec2-compatibility project."}, {'account_id': 14884, 'date': '2015-06-13 04:39:14.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

If EC2 is soon to be removed from tempest. Patch is not worthwhile.'}]

commit_message:
Make default ec2_api=False in compute-feature-enabled

Very often people struggle finding a way to skip
thirdparty boto tests. As it is not straight forward
because all thirdparty boto tests can only be skipped
by making ec2_api=False. Also, in a typical OpenStack
scenario, it is not very common to have ec2 enabled.
Hence it would be appropriate to default ec2_api as
'False'.

Change-Id: If52724460f5ab5e99f33fa7562ef16e45d99fe86

commit_message:
Port IPMI to Python 3

binascii.hexlify() returns a byte string whereas the code expects a
native string, so Unicode on Python 3. On Python 3, decode the string
from ASCII to get Unicode.

Enable ipmi tests in tox.ini on Python 3.4.

Change-Id: I154723ad42efb61a06b71600975374441920a852

Set .gitreview defaultbranch to feature/pecan

Set the default branch for the git review file
so the branch doesn't have to be specified with
the git review command.

commit_message:
spec: pin rspec-puppet to 1.0.1

rspec-puppet (2.0.0) was released yesterday[1], this new version broke
puppet-openstack unit tests (undefined method `resource')[2] as talked on
and in a second time to update your specs to 2.0.0 and rspec 3.x`)

[1] https://github.com/rodjek/rspec-puppet/commit/8459e14807977244c00bdbcf190062c529b63474
[2] http://logs.openstack.org/45/105245/6/check/gate-puppet-nova-puppet-unit-3.3/3682541/console.html

Change-Id: Ifa0d525232254c2b78815e31ecb6603c53507cd3
Partial-bug: #1417604

commit_message:
Remove "More Projects" link from the header

The link points to the Identity dashboard, and it breaks the whole
Horizon in case the Identity dashboard is disabled.

Change-Id: Ifd0501f7c4aa80388d63516b424215b37e8d7149
Closes-bug: #1399126

I would recommend to remove LBaaS API versions from class and methods names at all.

The main question is: how you are sure that LBaaS version is v1? I see only claas like self.clients("neutron").create_pool() - does that mean that LBaaS API v1 is in use? There is no validation provided.

Maybe calls signatures does not differ while using LBaaS from neutron client?'}, {'account_id': 14884, 'date': '2015-06-11 11:46:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31:

LBaaS v1 pools are created with /lb/pools/ while LBaaS v2 pools are created with /lbaas/pools/ https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron/LBaaS/API_2.0#Pools
While in the neutron client,
v1: create_pool(**args) https://github.com/openstack/python-neutronclient/blob/master/neutronclient/v2_0/client.py#L1065
v2: create_lbaas_pool(**args) https://github.com/openstack/python-neutronclient/blob/master/neutronclient/v2_0/client.py#L947'}, {'account_id': 13609, 'date': '2015-06-11 11:48:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31:

Then you know how you should name the appropriates in the Scenario:

_create_pool for v1 and _create_lbaas_pool for v2.

This is a bit confusing for the people outside of the Neutron project, yes.'}, {'account_id': 10475, 'date': '2015-06-11 11:49:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 31:

Approach proposed by Yair looks nice - let's add version only to class names"}, {'account_id': 14817, 'date': '2015-06-11 11:50:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 31: Verified+1

'}, {'created': '2015-06-11 09:06:47.000000000', 'message': 'Add Neutron Loadbalancer (LBaaS v1) create and list pool

Enable benchmarking of neutron loadbalancer v1 pool-create and pool-list.
LBaaS v1 uses path "lb/pools" and LBaaS v2 "lbaas/pools" thus
neutron differentiates v1 pools and v2 pools by lb and lbaas respectively.
Using the same convention in rally scenarios does not seem good, hence
I have used v1 to differentiate i.e. create_v1_pool, list_v1_pools and
create_and_list_v1_pools. This should not cause any problem in the future
enhancements.
More info on LBaaS v1 https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron/LBaaS/API_1.0
LBaaS v2 https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Neutron/LBaaS/API_2.0

commit_message:
Add Neutron Loadbalancer v1 create and list pool

Enable benchmarking of the Neutron LoadBalancer v1
pool-create and pool-list APIs. Due to the different
API scheme and confusing naming conventions in
Neutron (LB is v1 API and LBaaS for v2 API) the
appropriate code is explicitly marked with 'v1'
since this only implements the API v1 benchmarking.

Change-Id: If51f6286be49724c0bc4ae343815704f01153e97

[{'created': '2015-05-20 17:36:02.000000000', 'message': "Add Manila support and base benchmark for shares

Manila provides management of shared or distributed filesystems.
Add support of Manila project and benchmark for creation and deletion
of its main resource - 'share'.

List of changes:
- Add 'create_delete_shares' scenario.
- Add base class with methods required for any set of 'create_delete_shares'
scenario.
- Add context called 'manila'. It can create and delete 'share networks' and
'security services' for shares.

Features:
- Shares can be created w/o share networks (+ security services).
- Share networks can be autocreated as well as reused from existing cloud,
but static users are required.
- If autocreation of share networks is enabled then Manila will create one
for each network in OpenStack.
- If multiple share networks are created per tenant, they their usage will
be balanced.

Change-Id: Ie29be6162e788c880aea6816803c9ddea340bcf7

commit_message:
[Manila] Add base benchmark for list shares operation

List of changes:
- Added general support of Manila project.
- Added support of 'list' operation for shares.
- Added benchmark for listing of shares.
- Added two different manila jobs scripts that will be used for two
different Manila installtions. Current benchmark is used without changes in
both installations.

Change-Id: Ie29be6162e788c880aea6816803c9ddea340bcf7

commit_message:
Don't use devstack to setup our functional env

This adds a setup script for each tox functional target to start a
rabbitmq-server, qpidd or redis daemon dedicated for the functional
testing.

This script is responsible to spawn a preconfigured daemon needed for
the functional tests.

This also changes the gate script to just install the required packages
instead of setup a devstack.

This also fixes the zmq config options loading in tests

Closes-bug: #1442612

Change-Id: I27eb2c1d3d0ca67aa361c83e41372138e03d9bdd

Rather than delete the docs entirely can we just have a minimal one line doc that points users to the main akanda docs at http://akanda.readthedocs.org/en/latest/ ?

Also, if you do that, can you also rename the ./doc directory to ./docs?  Then we can have the same pointer in the readthedocs page for akanda-rug.

Itd be confusing for users who go looking for docs in this repo, if there was simply nothing there.'}, {'account_id': 6923, 'date': '2015-06-11 18:35:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1420, 'date': '2015-06-11 19:02:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

We need to preserve the docs source tree so sphinx builds still work:

* docs/README.rst should be docs/source/index.rst and properly RST formatted
* You need to keep conf.py in docs/source/conf.py
* tox.ini's doc target needs to be updated to point to the new ./docs/source instead of ./doc/source

You can make sure stuff is cool locally by running 'tox -e doc' and seeing that it produces a doc build in docs/build/html/"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-11 19:26:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Update the docs directory

State machine bits removed as
  they are moving to the akanda repo
Aslo fix bad URL in root readme

Partially Implements: blueprint liberty-doc-updates

Change-Id: I35cd688850fdd007bb9f0fb27759f6081e64d160

JSCS cleanup - style guide cleanup for modal

Following John Papa's style guide, this patch cleans up the
Angular code for the 'modal' module.

Change-Id: Ife8771db335a379be466e11ee448a35b9d870522
Partially-Implements: blueprint jscs-cleanup

commit_message:
Rename stackforge/mistral to openstack/mistral

* Move Mistral subprojects to openstack namespace
* Adding notifications for mistral-dashboard project
  to the team channel

Approved commit to governance repository:
    https://review.openstack.org/#/c/170225/

Depends-On: I5d0e877903c3f55ce2330e301b27da9435f677c5

commit_message:
Remove old Fuel plugins

Two of the Fuel plugins are no longer maintained and developed.
They should be removed (moved to stackforge-attic) to do not
confuse people.
Plugins that will be removed:
 * fuel-plugin-group-based-policy
 * fuel-plugin-external-nfs

Change-Id: Iabcc43885193cd2840c6605c47bde42b90cfa6f7

commit_message:
Move zvm-driver to stackforge-attic

zvm-driver have been splited to two projects, nova-zvm-virt-driver
and networking-zvm, so the old project is no longer being
maintained.

Change-Id: I3214c1d47c390f6d12cc08bcef0dbaebcf8ebee9

commit_message:
Move networking-odl into the openstack namespace

Per the new Neutron Stadium effort, this is moving under the openstack
namespace.

Related governance change: I81408301c78474f9da0bad23bf83bf6178160a9a

Change-Id: Ic0ce3e38dca0dd54098f56007be36fb84c31353d

subject: networking-ovn: move from stackforge/ to openstack/

commit_message:
Fix distributed router extension name

The name for network distributed router extension should be
'dist-router' instead of 'dvr'. Fix it in the DvrRoutersTest.

Closes-Bug: #1463492

I think the proper fix is to fix the callers of this method - although there's been a lot of churn in this section of neutron so this may have already occured, so please do correct me if I'm wrong"}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-03-03 19:40:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Maybe it's time to revive Sean's patch ;)

Seriously, maybe the best way forward is to abstract this mechanism and call the function send_neighbor_advertisement(), and it switches to ARP or ND (not now, but maybe later) based on the IP address passed.  The only stumbling block is that 'count' is passed as an argument - can we pass a config object?

Just a thought."}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-03-03 23:47:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Sean: Xu Han had proposed the same change earlier (see: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/114437/1/neutron/agent/l3_agent.py, I would have revived her change in this older review but it's Abandoned and I couldn't reopen it). The consensus then was that it was easier to leave the check in _send_gratuitous_arp_packet rather than have the callers do the checking. There are currently 4 callers:
  neutron/agent/l3/dvr_fip_ns.py
  neutron/agent/l3/legacy_router.py
  neutron/agent/l3/agent.py
  neutron/agent/l3/agent.py
We could move the check for address family to the callers, and that would be cleaner; but then to pass UT muster, we'd probably end up adding 3 or 4 test cases to check that the callers don't call _send_gratuitous_arp_packet for V6 cases. Seems like a good tradeoff to leave the check in one place, but I'm open for changing this."}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-03-04 15:07:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Brian: I didn't know Sean had a patch for this. This bug
seems to be getting around. :o/
If we go with approach of using an abstract/combined
method, I'm not sure passing an L3 driver config object
to the IP lib would be acceptable. Is the problem with
the count argument that it's v4-specific?  I would think
it would be okay to allow the callers send both v4 and
v6 specific arguments, if there are any, (or the caller
could send just one or the other based on context) and
let the abstract/combined method use whatever it needs.
For method name, I would prefer "send_gratuitous_arp_or_na" to "send_neighbor_advertisement" since the latter name is v6-leaning, IMO. However, we don't have the support to send
NAs yet, so that wouldn't work for now...
Maybe I'll try Sean's suggestion, and when we add support
for sending NAs, we can switch to using an abstract/combined
method.'}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-03-04 19:37:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-03-04 19:49:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 13409, 'date': '2015-03-04 19:50:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

This way it's safe to use if a new call is made to it, for example."}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-03-05 21:07:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

I guess I'd vote with Assaf and have the method check, since there seems to be new callers popping up and doing it in one place will catch them all."}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-03-05 21:26:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Assaf: The call to send_gratuitous_arp in legacy_router.py
is for floating IP addresses, so this should not get called
with IPv6 addresses. So no check is needed there.
I had thought the same for dvr_fip_ns.py (i.e since it's
called in the context of a FIP namespace, it should only
involve IPv4 addresses), but taking a second look, a
dual-stack external gateway could be used, possibly causing
a problem with the V6 address."}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-03-05 23:29:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2015-03-06 00:02:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

I think I would probably accept this patch if you resolve the merge conflict.  It is better than nothing.  Changing the name to include "_if_ipv4" does help a bit.  At least it tells us at the caller that something will happen only for ipv4.  My -1 is only to express the following while you resolve the merge conflict:

I think hiding a check like this deep in a method smells of some other problem.  I personally think that the code tries to lump ipv4 and ipv6 together and ignore the differences a little too much.  My reaction was the same as Sean's for this case because I expect code to know it shouldn't be sending gratuitous arp for ipv6.  I'd rather that code not request something that shouldn't be done expecting that some lower level library will ignore it if it isn't called right.  But, it might take some refactoring to get the kind of code that I really want.

I might even be happy if we created a better abstraction for the address family where some "announce new address" method used gratuitous arp for ipv4 and a no-op for ipv6 with a comment about why it isn't necessary.'}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2015-05-05 17:39:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I second the opinion that things like this should be decided earlier in the call flow.'}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-05-08 20:10:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 6695, 'date': '2015-05-08 20:22:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 14323, 'date': '2015-05-08 21:04:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-03-03 14:00:57.000000000', 'message': 'Stop sending gratuitous arp when ip version is 6

IPv4 uses the gratuitous arp mechanism both to provide "advance
notification" of MAC addresses (causes neighbors to add/update
their arp cache before they do an arp request), and to detect
address conflicts.

IPv6 uses the Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP) for address
resolution and for Duplicate Address Detection (DAD) instead
of ARP. For stateless networks (SLAAC or DHCPv6-stateless
subnets in OpenStack), IPv6 also uses routing advertisements
(RAs) to advertise available prefixes. These RAs have a
side benefit of causing an update of the neighbor cache
entry for the link local address of a gateway on each of
the neighbors.

This fix prevents calls to the arping utility for IPv6
addresses, thereby eliminating errors reported by arping
for IPv6 addresses.

The assumption is that NDP, DAD, and RAs are sufficient
for address resolution and duplicate address detection
for IPv6, and that unsolicited Neighbor Advertisements (NAs)
are not required for OpenStack services. If this turns out
not to be the case for some service/feature, then a separate
bug should be filed to add support for unsolicited NAs for
that service.

Change-Id: I14f869b7d488d7e691f7316eafcab3064e12cda6
Closes-Bug: 1357068

commit_message:
Stop sending gratuitous arp when ip version is 6

This fix prevents calls to the arping utility for IPv6
addresses, thereby eliminating errors reported by arping
for IPv6 addresses.

The assumption is that NDP, DAD, and RAs are sufficient
for address resolution and duplicate address detection
for IPv6, and that unsolicited Neighbor Advertisements (NAs)
are not required for OpenStack services. If this turns out
not to be the case for some service/feature, then a separate
bug should be filed to add support for unsolicited NAs for
that service.

Change-Id: I14f869b7d488d7e691f7316eafcab3064e12cda6
Closes-Bug: 1357068

commit_message:
Compile OpenStack deb packages from upstream source repositories during ISO build.

1) Add routines for building OpenStack deb packages and adding them to local mirror.
2) Change default value of BUILD_OPENSTACK_PACKAGES config variable.
3) Move components sources preparation stuff one level higher.
4) Add separate targets for building rpm and deb packages.

Change-Id: I815e2a02171559c92bbaf3251c9b763780552b5c

commit_message:
Python3: replace 'unicode' with 'six.text_type'

In Python 3, 'unicode' does not exist; 'six.text_type' should be used instead.

Change-Id: I71011b4beee9817a61278eb473804cfb798de74a
Blueprint: neutron-python3

commit_message:
Add drivers to the documentation

Use stevedore.sphinxext to populate a new page listing all available
drivers.

Add docstrings to the driver classes, including references to more
extensive documentation if it is available.

Depends-on: I1a24f9326b4e54174d9dc0ae366315fe29c3ac1b
Depends-on: Ie715f98fe0d3cba8b2f4f6235e7c2b6f79be7ea0

commit_message:
Remove deprecated code

Remove:
  * '$rally use' cli command entirely
  * Depraceted api: create_deploy, destroy_deploy, recreate_deploy,
    task_template_render, create_task, task_validate, start_task, abort_task,
    delete_task, verify, install_tempest.
  * Deployment cli parameter --uuid. '$rally deployment --uuid'
  * Task cli parameters --deploy-id, --uuid.
  * Show cli parameters --deploy-id.
  * Verify cli parameter --deploy-id.
  * Manage cli parameter --deploy-id.
  * Deprecated parameter from objects/endpoints.py admin_port.
  * FailureRateDeprecated class from plugins/common/sla/failure_rate.py
  * Depraceted parameters min_size, max_size, volime_size at plugins/
    openstack/scenarios/cinder/volumes.py. Now U should use size dict argument instead.
  * Functional test for 'use' cli comamnd tests/functional/test_cli_use.py

Fix unit tests after this work was done.

Change-Id: Ibac6cdac49fa8afeaefd299fa3c0c6b0952abfb0
